(1, 'Are ''Flat-Pack'' Homes The Solution To The Housing Shortage?', '“Flat-pack” houses could end Britain’s housing crisis which is pushing property prices beyond many first-time buyers’ reach, causing them to abandon hopes of home ownership.', '<p>&ldquo;Flat-pack&rdquo; houses could end Britain&rsquo;s housing crisis which is pushing property prices beyond many first-time buyers&rsquo; reach, causing them to abandon hopes of home ownership.</p>\r\n<p>Embracing &ldquo;modular homes&rdquo;, where large parts of a property are manufactured in factories and then transported to building sites for final assembly, would speed up house building, according to the&nbsp;<a href="http://www.imeche.org/" target="_blank">Institution of Mechanical Engineers</a>&nbsp;(IME).</p>\r\n<p>In a&nbsp;<a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/property/11716733/www.imeche.org/docs/default-source/position-statements/uk-house-building-manufacturing-affordable-quality-homes-policy-statemen.pdf?sfvrsn=0" target="_blank">new report</a>&nbsp;the body argues that modular homes would help the UK build the 250,000 new homes needed each year for the next two decades as the population booms, compared with the current rate of about 120,000.</p>\r\n<p>Dr Tim Fox, author of the IME study, called for the Government to support off-site construction technology with incentives, saying that as well as providing a greater number of homes because modular construction is faster, they also deliver more environmentally friendly properties.</p>\r\n<p>More efficient, modern construction in factories rather than using bricks and mortar on site means modular homes use fewer resources to build and are more energy efficient once completed.</p>\r\n<p>As well as delivering cheaper homes, flat-pack homes could also boost the country&rsquo;s manufacturing and skills base, the IME added.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;The UK is in the middle of an acute housing crisis,&rdquo; said Dr Fox. &ldquo;The Government needs to demonstrate real ambition, leadership and innovation, not make small piecemeal changes, if it is going to solve the UK&rsquo;s housing crisis. Overhauling the way the UK constructs homes could be the quickest and most effective way of doing this.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>He added that modular construction has moved on since post-war prefabricated homes and controversial &ldquo;system-built&rdquo; houses of the 1960s and 1970s.</p>\r\n<p>Changing the way Britain build its homes won the support of the Home Builders Federation (HBF), which said Britain is a among the world''s leaders in the modular construction.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;It is not just about making prefabs anymore,&rdquo; said a HBF spokesman. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s manufacturing process that is very high quality and brings great advantages. Anything we can do to solve the housing crisis is needed and this is just one way of speeding up the construction process.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong><a href="../../team_members/36">Chris Sellars<br /></a></strong>Solicitor, Executive Director, Head of Residential Property Services</p>\r\n<p>Banner Jones Solicitors<br />24 Glumangate<br />Chesterfield<br />Tel 01246 560560<br />Fax 01246 220390<br />Email:&nbsp;<a href="mailto:info@bannerjones.co.uk">info@bannerjones.co.uk</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.facebook.com/BannerJonesSolicitors" target="_blank"><img src="../../../assets/articles/368/contained_images/65cc94c2d802_449_rsz_facebook.png?1436458081" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="26" /></a>&nbsp;<a href="http://plus.google.com/+bannerjones" target="_blank"><img src="../../../assets/articles/368/contained_images/08e9d81a3b98_444_rsz_googleplus.png?1436280698" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="26" /></a>&nbsp;<a href="http://www.linkedin.com/company/1134191" target="_blank"><img src="../../../assets/articles/368/contained_images/1dd408cd3426_445_rsz_linkedin.png?1436280705" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="26" /></a>&nbsp;<a href="http://twitter.com/bannerjones" target="_blank"><img src="../../../assets/articles/368/contained_images/54fe569ec084_447_rsz_twitter.png?1436280719" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="26" /></a>&nbsp;<a href="http://www.youtube.com/channel/UCxXn4FxKr5OyKwcbhlekSwg" target="_blank"><img src="../../../assets/articles/368/contained_images/1f5c4638019c_450_YouTube.jpeg?1436520453" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="26" /></a></p>', '2015-07-07', '401_SellarsMarket.png', 'image/png', 202466, '2015-07-13 14:37:39', '', '2015-07-13 14:37:40', '2015-07-15 11:44:22', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(2, 'The Housing Market is Hotting Up...', '...or at least so said the high street banks last Friday. Figures showed the number of borrowers taking mortgages to buy homes reached a 15-month high in June.', '<p>...or at least so said the high street banks last Friday. Figures showed the number of borrowers taking mortgages to buy homes reached a 15-month high in June. The figures came ahead of a Treasury announcement that six providers had signed up to offer it''s help to buy Isa from December &ndash; the latest strand in the government&rsquo;s efforts to help first-time buyers keep up with rising prices.</p>\r\n<p>Together with the end of political uncertainty following the election, fierce competition among mortgage lenders has driven rates to record lows, and this seems to have renewed homebuyers&rsquo; confidence, and encouraged remortgaging. A total of 44,488 loans were taken out for house purchases in June, an uplift of 8% on the same month in 2014 and above the previous six-month average of 39,340.</p>\r\n<p>The total number of approvals was almost 10,000 more than the six-month average, as Richard Woolhouse, chief economist at the British Bankers Association said: &ldquo;The housing market is beginning to hot up again, with a pick-up in the number of mortgage approvals for the last month.</p>\r\n<p>Interestingly, we&rsquo;ve also seen an increase in the number of people remortgaging, which could be down to savvy borrowers taking advantage of competitive deals on fixed-rate mortgages ahead of a possible rise in interest rates. There are some great deals out there; for instance First Direct are offering a lifetime tracker at 1.99% over base rate ie 2.49%. If interest rates go up the mortgage will just match the base rate rise, not any other rise in mortgage rates.</p>\r\n<p>The figures are for a period <a href="http://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/jul/16/uk-interest-rate-rise-new-year">before the Bank of England governor&rsquo;s recent warning that interest rates could rise at the turn of the year</a>, which is likely to prompt more borrowers to consider locking in at current low rates.</p>\r\n<p>Anecdotally, the first rate rise is the trigger point for many people remortgaging but it may even be the second or third increase, as that is when there is a significant impact on a household&rsquo;s expenditure and people then remortgage to &lsquo;save&rsquo; money. However, by then the best fixed rates will have long gone.</p>\r\n<p>For would-be buyers, <a href="http://www.theguardian.com/money/2015/mar/18/how-will-osbornes-help-to-buy-isa-work-for-first-time-buyers">the help to buy Isa</a> will offer a government payment of &pound;50 for every &pound;200 saved by each person, up to a maximum of &pound;3,000, or &pound;6,000 for couples who buy together. The Treasury said the Isa would be available from 1 December, with Barclays, Lloyds Banking Group, Nationwide, NatWest, Santander, and Virgin Money already committed to offering the accounts.</p>\r\n<p>The chancellor, George Osborne, said he was &ldquo;delighted&rdquo; that so many providers had signed up. &ldquo;This government is determined to help working people, and encouraging the aspiration to home ownership is central to that,&rdquo; he said.</p>\r\n<p>The accounts, which will be available for four years and can be used at any point, are available to all first-time buyers and can be used alongside other government schemes.</p>\r\n<p>Research by Halifax suggests savers will need all the help they can get. It found that the average price paid for homes bought through both parts of <a href="http://www.theguardian.com/money/2015/jun/15/help-to-buy-locks-out-first-time-buyers-house-prices">Help-to-buy</a> and the shared ownership scheme has hit &pound;190,000 &ndash; only 4% less than the average amount for ordinary house prices. The lender said the schemes were helping younger buyers, with a third of those using them aged 20 to 29.</p>\r\n<p>With Mark Carney&rsquo;s announcement that base rate is likely to rise in the near future, these low rates will not be around for long. Borrowers still sitting on their SVR or coming to the end of a fixed mortgage deal need to act fast to secure a low rate.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong><a href="../../team_members/36">Chris Sellars<br /></a></strong>Solicitor, Executive Director, Head of Residential Property Services</p>\r\n<p>Banner Jones Solicitors<br />24 Glumangate<br />Chesterfield<br />Tel 01246 560560<br />Fax 01246 220390<br />Email:&nbsp;<a href="mailto:info@bannerjones.co.uk">info@bannerjones.co.uk</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.facebook.com/BannerJonesSolicitors" target="_blank"><img src="../../../assets/articles/368/contained_images/65cc94c2d802_449_rsz_facebook.png?1436458081" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="26" /></a>&nbsp;<a href="http://plus.google.com/+bannerjones" target="_blank"><img src="../../../assets/articles/368/contained_images/08e9d81a3b98_444_rsz_googleplus.png?1436280698" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="26" /></a>&nbsp;<a href="http://www.linkedin.com/company/1134191" target="_blank"><img src="../../../assets/articles/368/contained_images/1dd408cd3426_445_rsz_linkedin.png?1436280705" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="26" /></a>&nbsp;<a href="http://twitter.com/bannerjones" target="_blank"><img src="../../../assets/articles/368/contained_images/54fe569ec084_447_rsz_twitter.png?1436280719" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="26" /></a>&nbsp;<a href="http://www.youtube.com/channel/UCxXn4FxKr5OyKwcbhlekSwg" target="_blank"><img src="../../../assets/articles/368/contained_images/1f5c4638019c_450_YouTube.jpeg?1436520453" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="26" /></a></p>', '2015-08-06', '401_SellarsMarket.png', 'image/png', 202466, '2015-08-10 09:15:42', '', '2015-08-10 09:15:44', '2015-08-10 09:15:44', 2, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(3, 'The Generation Gap ', 'Many of us are lucky enough to own our own homes, but worry about how our children will ever manage to do the same. ', '<p>Many of us are lucky enough to own our own homes, but worry about how our children will ever manage to do the same. My parents bought their first house in 1963. Back then, the average first home cost &pound;4,000 (theirs cost &pound;2000) and you would typically have been able to buy it <a href="http://www.mortgagestrategy.co.uk/news-and-features/latest-news/borrowers-stay-in-first-homes-for-14-years1075689.article">at the tender age of 25</a>&nbsp;- my parents were 24 and 20.</p>\r\n<p>Not any more. Now just 8% of 25-year-olds make it on to the property ladder, the <a href="http://www.cml.org.uk/news/723/">Council of Mortgage Lenders</a> says. The average price of a first home has increased by 5,225% over the past 52 years, to &pound;209,000. This has massively outpaced the incomes of first-time buyers, which have grown at less than half that rate. <a href="http://england.shelter.org.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0004/1076926/2015_02_26_Affordability_for_first_time_buyers_-_FINAL.pdf">Shelter</a> estimates that today&rsquo;s first-time buyers spend 30% to 40% more to buy their first home today than they would have done in 1963.</p>\r\n<p>What has driven these dramatic changes in home ownership &ndash; and will any other generation ever have it so good again?</p>\r\n<p>By 1971, growth in homeownership meant that an equal number of people rented as owned their homes &ndash; but by 1981 the number of owner-occupiers <a href="http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/census/2011-census-analysis/a-century-of-home-ownership-and-renting-in-england-and-wales/short-story-on-housing.html">had risen to 58%</a>, according to the Office of National Statistics.</p>\r\n<p>At around that time Margaret Thatcher launched the <a href="http://www.theguardian.com/money/blog/2015/apr/18/right-to-buy-council-houses-wrong">Right To Buy scheme</a>, enabling council house tenants to buy their own homes. The legislation was passed in 1980 and was a response to a rise in incomes, argues Professor Colin Jones at Heriot-Watt University&rsquo;s School of The Built Environment: &ldquo;Rising incomes meant that more people were demanding home ownership and so some sort of scheme was inevitable. There was also none of the supply-side problem we have today, so councils felt perfectly comfortable selling off the stock.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Supply was so abundant that, even adjusting for general inflation, properties were mostly selling at less than their rebuilding cost.</p>\r\n<p>More than a third of property wealth in the UK is now owned by households where at least one occupant is 65 or older, and nearly one in 10 (9%) of 55- to 64-year-olds live in households with net property wealth of &pound;500,000 or more; the highest of any age group, says the <a href="http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/was/wealth-in-great-britain-wave-3/2010-2012/report--chapter-3--property-wealth.html?format=print">ONS</a>.</p>\r\n<p>Already, <a href="http://www.ifs.org.uk/uploads/publications/comms/r96.pdf">28% of those aged 22 to 30 years of age</a> have been forced to remain at their family home, or move back. Statistics from <a href="http://www.cih.org/news-article/display/vpathDCR/templatedata/cih/news-article/data/Young_people_and_people_on_lower_incomes_paying_the_price_for_our_broken_housing_market">the Chartered Institute of Housing</a> (CHS) show that home ownership among 25- to 34-year-olds has plummeted from 67% in 1991 to 26% in 2013 whilst ownership among those aged 65 to 74 has increased from 62% to 77%. In 1981 this figure stood at just 49%.</p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.imla.org.uk/news/post.php?s=2015-04-10-average-home-changes-hands-every-23-years---almost-three-times-longer-than-in-the-1980s">A recent report from the Intermediary Mortgage Lenders Association</a> accused baby boomers of &ldquo;hoarding&rdquo; large family homes, contributing to inertia in the market that keeps aspiring buyers off the property ladder. Meanwhile the CHS warned of a &ldquo;perfect storm&rdquo; where older, already privileged homeowners buy and rent homes to those priced out of ownership.</p>\r\n<p>Many people in the baby boomer generation will struggle to recognise themselves in this description of an asset-rich, privileged few. A sizeable number of retirees shoulder financial responsibility for both their adult children and elderly parents. Research from the Equity Release Council (ERC) shows that over-55s contributed around &pound;26.7bn to support children and grandchildren last year. Helping with a house purchase was the most common reason for financial assistance, with retirees stumping up an average of &pound;14,065.</p>\r\n<p><a href="http://uk.prweb.com/releases/2014/11/prweb12324667.htm">Research by Prudential</a> found that 41% of over-55s plan to sell their current home, with around 2.5 million of those <a href="http://www.theguardian.com/money/2015/jul/28/downsizing-for-retirement-real-stories">planning to downsize</a>. The average amount of cash these last-time buyers hope to free up is &pound;87,600 and many will feel pressure to use at least some of that money to help their adult children.</p>\r\n<p>In reality, many of those approaching pensionable age are not selling their homes to help their children onto the property ladder, but to fund their own retirement. <a href="http://www.lv.com/retirement-plan/love-retirement/home-and-garden/hippies-funding-their-retirement">Research from LV=</a> showed that 52% of people aged 60 and over are considering freeing up money from their properties to pay for retirement.</p>\r\n<p>But while this may get recent retirees out of the red, when downsizers sell to younger families, these buyers burden themselves by buying at massive prices compared to what the sellers paid, by taking on record levels of mortgage debt.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong><a href="../../team_members/36">Chris Sellars<br /></a></strong>Solicitor, Executive Director, Head of Residential Property Department</p>\r\n<p>Banner Jones Solicitors<br />24 Glumangate<br />Chesterfield<br />Tel 01246 560560<br />Fax 01246 220390<br />Email:&nbsp;<a href="mailto:info@bannerjones.co.uk">info@bannerjones.co.uk</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.facebook.com/BannerJonesSolicitors" target="_blank"><img src="../../../assets/articles/368/contained_images/65cc94c2d802_449_rsz_facebook.png?1436458081" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="26" /></a>&nbsp;<a href="http://plus.google.com/+bannerjones" target="_blank"><img src="../../../assets/articles/368/contained_images/08e9d81a3b98_444_rsz_googleplus.png?1436280698" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="26" /></a>&nbsp;<a href="http://www.linkedin.com/company/1134191" target="_blank"><img src="../../../assets/articles/368/contained_images/1dd408cd3426_445_rsz_linkedin.png?1436280705" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="26" /></a>&nbsp;<a href="http://twitter.com/bannerjones" target="_blank"><img src="../../../assets/articles/368/contained_images/54fe569ec084_447_rsz_twitter.png?1436280719" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="26" /></a>&nbsp;<a href="http://www.youtube.com/channel/UCxXn4FxKr5OyKwcbhlekSwg" target="_blank"><img src="../../../assets/articles/368/contained_images/1f5c4638019c_450_YouTube.jpeg?1436520453" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="26" /></a></p>', '2015-08-20', '401_SellarsMarket.png', 'image/png', 202466, '2015-08-17 13:46:26', '', '2015-08-17 13:46:27', '2015-08-26 08:49:49', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(4, 'Higher Fines For Rogue Landlords In Rental Market Shakeup ', 'Rogue landlords and letting agents face higher fines, being potentially blacklisted from the property industry and being forced to repay rent taken since the start of a tenancy under proposals outlined by the government this week.', '<p>Rogue landlords and letting agents face higher fines, being potentially blacklisted from the property industry and being forced to <a href="../../page/debt-recovery-business" target="_blank">repay rent </a>taken since the start of a tenancy under proposals outlined by the government this week.</p>\r\n<p>One aspect of the plans &ndash; the eviction of immigrants living illegally in Britain &ndash; attracted the most headlines, but other proposals suggest that the government is considering a transformation of the private rental market.</p>\r\n<p>The Department for Communities and Local Government has said that the existing level of fines is failing to have an impact and is just written off as a business expense. Proposals in the DCLG&rsquo;s &ldquo;Tackling rogue landlords and improving the private rental sector&rdquo; paper include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>A blacklist of rogue landlords and letting agents.</li>\r\n<li>Minimum fines for repeat offences and rent repayment orders.</li>\r\n<li>New powers for local authorities to seize private rentals.</li>\r\n<li>A &ldquo;fit and proper person&rdquo; test for landlords.</li>\r\n<li>New civil penalties and fines against landlords for overcrowding, damp, disrepair and vermin infestations.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>The proposals come amid growing concern over the state of the private rented sector. The DCLG said 84% of private renters are satisfied with their accommodation, but that a small number of rogue landlords are causing &ldquo;acute and complex problems&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p>When the government gave &pound;6.7m to a few local authorities to inspect 40,000 privately rented properties, they found 3,000 were so poor that enforcement action or prosecution were required.</p>\r\n<p>Magistrates are, in theory, able to impose unlimited fines against landlords but, in practice, the average is just &pound;1,500 as the courts have to take into account the means of the offender. It found that one landlord was fined less than &pound;1,500 for operating an unlicensed HMO (house in multiple occupation) that was &ldquo;severely overcrowded and in extremely poor condition&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p>Rent repayment orders were introduced in 2004 but few have been issued. The DCLG is suggesting a wider definition of the law, which could mean that a landlord who fails to comply with local authority orders on things such as damp could be forced to repay all the rent they have received.</p>\r\n<p>But it is the proposals for new civil penalties that could have the biggest impact on landlords. Prosecutions are rare as few local authorities have the resources to take landlords to court. But civil penalties (along the lines of parking tickets) could be issued without recourse to the courts and applied easily and widely.</p>\r\n<p>The DCLG said civil penalties could be issued against landlords and letting agents who permit overcrowding and let properties fall into disrepair, as well as for poor sanitation, electrical faults, damp and vermin infestation. Fines could be as high as &pound;5,000.</p>\r\n<p>The campaign group Generation Rent has welcomed many of the proposals. A spokesman says: &ldquo;It was a shame the immigration checks led the coverage as there are a number of policies the government is proposing that we have been calling for, such as sharing tenancy deposit data to help with enforcement, the ability for councils to levy fines they can keep and expanding rent repayment orders. These will make it easier for authorities to target criminal landlords, easier to bring them to justice and easier to protect tenants from unsafe housing&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p>But letting agents say the new regulations will be just another burden on legitimate businesses and will fail to catch persistent offenders.</p>\r\n<p>Others initiatives to control rogue landlords or improve practices have largely flopped, say critics.</p>\r\n<p>A scheme launched by the London mayor, <a href="http://twitter.com/MayorofLondon" target="_blank">Boris Johnson</a>, to improve the standard of rented property in the capital was branded a flop after it was found just that 0.2% of adverts for homes to let mentioned that the landlord or letting agent had signed up.</p>\r\n<p>Since October last year, letting agents have been required to tell tenants about which ombudsman redress scheme they have joined, but many have failed to sign up and have faced little or no enforcement action.</p>\r\n<p>A spokesman for the Association of Residential Letting Agents says: &ldquo;We are staunch advocates of any moves to improve standards in the private rented sector and welcome the consultation.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong><a href="../../team_members/36">Chris Sellars<br /></a></strong>Solicitor, Executive Director, Head of Residential Property Department</p>\r\n<p>Banner Jones Solicitors<br />24 Glumangate<br />Chesterfield<br />Tel 01246 560560<br />Fax 01246 220390<br />Email:&nbsp;<a href="mailto:info@bannerjones.co.uk">info@bannerjones.co.uk</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.facebook.com/BannerJonesSolicitors" target="_blank"><img src="../../../assets/articles/368/contained_images/65cc94c2d802_449_rsz_facebook.png?1436458081" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="26" /></a>&nbsp;<a href="http://plus.google.com/+bannerjones" target="_blank"><img src="../../../assets/articles/368/contained_images/08e9d81a3b98_444_rsz_googleplus.png?1436280698" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="26" /></a>&nbsp;<a href="http://www.linkedin.com/company/1134191" target="_blank"><img src="../../../assets/articles/368/contained_images/1dd408cd3426_445_rsz_linkedin.png?1436280705" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="2