(1, 'Network & Nosh, Family Business Advice', 'Mixing Family and Business can be very complex and it’s often hard to keep things fair and equal.  Our Family Business Team will be the guest speaker at this event, hoested by Natwest and DNCC.  Stephen, Sarah and Toby will give some expert advice on the common issues faced by Family Owned Businesses including succession planning, remuneration and asset protection.\r\n\r\n', '<p>The format for the event will be:</p>\r\n<p>12.00:&nbsp;Arrival &amp; Networking<br />12.25:&nbsp;Welcome<br />12.30:&nbsp;Lunch &amp; Networking<br />13.30:&nbsp;Guest Speakers Stephen Gordon, Sarah Nadin and Toby Netting<br />13.55: Closing remarks <br />14.00:&nbsp;End</p>\r\n<p>The cost of attending this networking lunch will be &pound;20.00 + VAT per person.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;To book your place(s) please email <a href="mailto:events@dncc.co.uk">events@dncc.co.uk</a> and an invoice will be sent out to request payment.</p>', '2011-06-16', '2011-06-17', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '2011-03-02 14:49:01', '2011-06-03 13:33:11', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(2, 'Care Fees Planning Seminar in conjunction with Age Concern', 'This FREE event is for anyone looking for more information on how to plan effectively for long term care.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe seminar will take place at Chesterfield Hotel at 2-4pm and light refreshments will be provided.\r\n', '<p>The seminar will tell you about:</p>\r\n<p><br />1.&nbsp; What Care can Cost ?<br />2.&nbsp; What help is available from the State ?<br />3.&nbsp; The Financial Assessment<br />4.&nbsp; How to Hang onto Your House<br />5.&nbsp; How to cover the cost of care<br />6.&nbsp; Handling someone else&rsquo;s affairs<br />7.&nbsp; Wills &amp; Trusts</p>\r\n<p>If you would like to join us on the day please e-mail <a href="mailto:aml@bannerjones.co.uk">aml@bannerjones.co.uk</a> to reserve your place.&nbsp; You are more than welcome to bring a friend or partner.</p>', '2011-09-07', '2011-09-07', '75_iStock_000005717962XSmall.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 204931, '2011-08-08 09:13:50', '', '2011-08-08 09:13:51', '2011-08-08 09:18:18', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(3, '3rd Family Business Forum- Employment law', 'If you own or are part of a family owned business and would like to meet with like minded people in an informal way, why not come along to our 3rd Family Business Forum?\r\n\r\nWe are delighted to inform you that our guest speaker for this forum is our very own Employment Law expert Trevor Hughes.  Trevor will be talking about how to manage staff and be there to answer any HR/employment issues you have.', '<p>Our specialist Family Business Team will also be on hand to answer any family business related legal questions you have.</p>\r\n<p>The forum will take place&nbsp;between &nbsp;6pm-9pm on Monday 26th September at the family owned Calabria restaurant on Glumangate.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Food and refreshments will be provided.</p>\r\n<p>To reserve your place at this event please e-mail <a href="mailto:aml@bannerjones.co.uk">aml@bannerjones.co.uk</a>&nbsp; You are more than welcome to bring along a friend, family member&nbsp;or colleague.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '2011-09-26', '2011-09-26', '117_Feb 2nd.JPG', 'image/jpeg', 283331, '2011-08-08 09:43:14', '', '2011-08-08 09:43:15', '2011-08-08 09:43:15', 2, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(4, 'Ask the Expert', 'Come and speak to one of our experts next Wednesday on the Market in Chesterfield.\r\n\r\nBanner Jones are taking part in the ''Ask the Expert'' event which is being organised by the Derbyshire Times.  The event allows you to come along and speak to industry experts from all sectors free of charge.\r\n\r\nThe event starts at 11am-3pm on the Market Square near Boots.', '', '2011-10-26', '2011-10-26', '71_iStock_000004583601XSmall.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 108950, '2011-10-19 15:31:13', '', '2011-10-19 15:31:14', '2011-10-19 15:39:14', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(5, '4th Family Business Forum', 'Are you part of a Family Owned Business?\r\n\r\nWould you like the chance to meet like minded people who share similar business issues? \r\n\r\nCome along to our 4th highly successful Family Business Forum, it’s free!,\r\n\r\nInformal networking,	 \r\n\r\nSpecialist family business advisers on hand,\r\n\r\nDelicious food,   \r\n\r\nInteresting guest speakers,    \r\n\r\nGreat atmosphere,     \r\n\r\nChance to share and discuss specific family issues,      \r\n\r\nNo hard sell.\r\n', '<p>Our guest speakers are Chartered Accountants BHP who will discuss various current issues that may affect your business.</p>\r\n<p>Come and join us:</p>\r\n<p>Date: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Monday 27<sup>th</sup> February</p>\r\n<p>Venue:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;Calabria, 30 Glumangate, Chesterfield, S40 1TX</p>\r\n<p>Time:&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 6- 8pm</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;Delicious Italian food and refreshments will be provided.&nbsp; Free car parking is available for guests although we would appreciate it if you could let us know in advance if you require this.&nbsp; If you would like to reserve a place (or two) at the forum please call Dawn Mann on 01246 560 560 or email <a href="mailto:dm@bannerjones.co.uk">dm@bannerjones.co.uk</a>.&nbsp; Places are limited so please let us know as soon as you can.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '2012-02-27', '2012-02-27', 'guests dining.JPG', 'image/pjpeg', 281634, '2012-02-01 11:31:59', '', '2012-02-01 11:32:05', '2012-02-03 16:30:47', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(6, 'International Trade Breakfast Forum', 'This free breakfast event aims to give new and growing exporters throughout the area some guidance and sources of help for expanding in to international trade.\r\n\r\nHearing from professionals in International Trade, the event aims to provide you with a forum to pose questions. As well as the speakers you will learn from other exporters in the audience. The event is being delivered by Banner Jones, NatWest Bank and Shorts Chartered Accountants with the support of the DNCC (Derbyshire and Nottinghamshire Chamber) and UK Trade & Investment.\r\n\r\nA range of subjects will be covered including, identifying export opportunities and strengthening your presence abroad, financing export growth, legal requirements for trading overseas, help with logistics and shipping and access to help with taxation questions\r\n', '<p>Venue : Chesterfield Proact Stadium</p>\r\n<p>Time: 8.00-10.00am</p>\r\n<p>Price:&nbsp; Free</p>\r\n<p>To book your free place contact the DNCC Events team on 01332 851280 or email <span class="rsmMailTo"><a href="mailto:events@dncc.co.uk">events@dncc.co.uk</a></span></p>', '2013-02-26', '2013-02-26', '77_iStock_000005896679XSmall.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 115487, '2013-02-19 09:39:21', '', '2013-02-19 09:39:21', '2013-02-19 09:41:14', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(7, 'Taking Control of Your Future', 'Discover the real answers about your future wealth from two of Derbyshire’s  leading experts...\r\n\r\nThursday 6th June 8-10am\r\nProact Stadium, Chesterfield\r\nRegistration and Breakfast 8am. Start 8.30am\r\n\r\n', '<p><strong>Here&rsquo;s what you can expect to learn from our free seminar:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Why you should never let your finances drift&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>The things you need to know before hiring a financial advisor </li>\r\n<li>When should you be retiring? It could be sooner than you think</li>\r\n<li>Discover how we are all the same when it comes to risk </li>\r\n<li>How to protect your assets from the tax man </li>\r\n<li>Why no two Wills are the same. Do you have the right one?</li>\r\n<li>How to protect your children&rsquo;s inheritance - find out how much they could be exposed if you don&rsquo;t&nbsp; </li>\r\n<li>And any other questions you would like answered by experts...</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Who should attend this seminar?&nbsp; YOU.&nbsp; Anyone who would like to ensure that their assets and wealth are being properly managed and protected.</p>\r\n<p>This event will be hosted by Banner Jones Solicitors and Banner Jones Wealth Management.</p>\r\n<p><img style="float: left;" src="../../..//assets/events/7/contained_images/0a699cbd3d48_178_BJ_WEALTH_MANAGEMENT_WHITE.JPG?1363685036" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" width="250" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Our expert speakers will include:</p>\r\n<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Sarah &nbsp;Nadin TEP- Private Client Solicitor </span></strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Sarah is a Director and Private Client Solicitor, she is also the head of the Private Client Department and a member of the Family Business Team. Sarah deals with the administration of a deceased''s estate (probate), the creation and administration of trusts, powers of attorney, application to the Court of Protection, inheritance tax and asset preservation planning and preparation of Wills.<br />&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Jillian Thomas- DipPFS &nbsp;Independent Financial Planner</span></strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Jill has over 30 years experience in financial services and is one of the industry&rsquo;s most well-respected figures, with a reputation stretching all the way into the heart of the City. <br />&ldquo;It is a privilege to be entrusted to look after people&rsquo;s financial affairs, no different to being asked to care for their health or their children&rsquo;s education. It&rsquo;s a position of trust and must be respected as such.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>To book your place&nbsp;simply fill out of the booking form below. If you have any queries regarding the event please contact <a href="mailto:aml@bannerjones.co.uk">aml@bannerjones.co.uk</a>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '2013-06-06', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2013-05-08 11:09:38', '2013-05-13 09:35:44', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(8, 'Route to Growth...', 'A focus on Manufacturing Excellence\r\n\r\nFREE Breakfast Seminar\r\n\r\n14th November 8-10am\r\nProact Stadium, Chesterfield\r\n\r\n\r\nHosted by the Manufacturing and Trade Group', '<p>Following our International Trade Forum earlier this year, The Manufacturing &amp; Trade Group supported by Banner Jones Solicitors, Shorts Accountants and NatWest are bringing you another great manufacturing and engineering event, with two excellent guest speakers confirmed.</p>\r\n<p>Our Guest Speaker&nbsp;Profiles:</p>\r\n<h2>Martin Allen, Manager<br />Manufacturing Technology Partnerships<br />Rolls Royce plc</h2>\r\n<p><img src="../../../assets/events/8/contained_images/bde32d28b961_193_Martin Allen crop.png?1376557139" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" width="134" height="143" /></p>\r\n<p class="a" style="text-align: justify;">Martin is a Chartered Physicist with 25+ years experience in capability acquisition for Rolls-Royce plc.&nbsp; He&nbsp;joined Rolls-Royce as a Graduate Apprentice, early career working as a Technologist to develop x-ray, neutron and laser measurement systems, followed by control and licensing of intellectual property, and currently responsible for establishing and maintaining an integrated network of university-based partners for manufacturing capability acquisition.</p>\r\n<p class="a" style="text-align: justify;">The success of the Advanced Manufacturing Research Centre in the UK has precipitated the creation of six similar and complimentary centres globally, resulting in substantial benefits for all collaborators and stake holders<strong>.</strong></p>\r\n<h2>Alex Mardapittas, Managing Director <br /><a href="http://ems-uk.org/energy-saving-technologies" target="_blank">EMSc (UK) Limited</a></h2>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<img src="../../../assets/events/8/contained_images/4c72997aeb2c_194_Alex mardapittas.png?1376557177" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" width="196" height="162" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>BEng, PhD, CEng, MIET, MEI Managing Director and Powerstar Designer</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Alex studied at Kings College London and then at Brunel University. On completing his research fellowship for Manufacturing Metrology in 1993, he went on to work in professional computer software training and development. As an experienced Chartered Engineer, with a research doctorate, he possesses an extensive knowledge of software programming and innovative engineering design, which has allowed him to provide award-winning solutions to the marketplace.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-family: Arial; color: #990000;">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-family: Arial; color: #990000;">Join us on 14th November for what will be a very interesting&nbsp;and&nbsp;informative event.<br class="sp_br" /><br class="sp_br" />Venue:&nbsp; Proact Stadium, Chesterfield<br class="sp_br" />Time:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 8am registration and breakfast<br class="sp_br" />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;8.30am presentations<br class="sp_br" />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 9.30am&nbsp; Q&amp;A to&nbsp;the speakers and a panel of experts<br class="sp_br" />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 10am Finish</span></p>', '2013-11-14', '2013-11-14', 'MT_GROUP_LOGO.jpg', 'image/pjpeg', 648022, '2013-09-30 11:18:18', '', '2013-08-12 13:51:33', '2013-09-30 11:20:05', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(9, 'Employment Law Update', 'WARNING- Not keeping up with Employment Law changes could damage your business.\r\n\r\nThis FREE breakfast seminar will ensure you that your business is not at risk due to recent changes in legislation.\r\n', '<p>Trevor Hughes is one of the best employment solicitors in the area.&nbsp; Trevor will update you on all of the recent changes to employment law including:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Compromise &amp; Settlement Agreements</li>\r\n<li>Tribunal changes- costs and fees</li>\r\n<li>Time Limits</li>\r\n<li>TUPE</li>\r\n<li>CRB Checks and Disclosures</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Proposals for 2014...</p>\r\n<p>Places are limited so early booking is advisable</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Venue:&nbsp; Calabria. Glumangate, Chesterfield</p>\r\n<p>Time:&nbsp; 8am Registration and Breakfast</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 8.30am Presentation</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 9am Questions for a 9.30am finish</p>', '2013-10-24', '2013-10-24', 'Trevor web.jpg', 'image/pjpeg', 27204, '2013-09-24 14:50:08', '', '2013-09-24 14:50:09', '2013-09-24 14:53:53', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(10, 'Investment Market Predictions with Justin Urquhart Stewart', 'Banner Jones would like to invite you to hear from two of the UK''s leading investment commentators, as to what they predict for Investment Markets for 2014.  Justin Urquhart Stewart, founder of Seven Investment Management and Jillian Thomas, Partner of Banner Jones Wealth Management are regulars on the television/ radio and in just one hour they will guide you through  their predications for the investments markets and tell you how you can make an investment returns in 2014.', '<p style="text-align: justify;">A note from Jillian Thomas: &ldquo;2013 commenced with the US teetering on the edge of the Fiscal Cliff; in the UK, the lights had just gone out on the last Comet store, the national high street was in disarray and the prophets of doom were muttering about a triple-dip recession.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">There were no more financial earthquakes, most of the world&rsquo;s major stock markets enjoyed noteworthy rises and the year even ended with Spain seeing its credit rating lifted.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Of course, there are still problems. Youth unemployment in Europe remains at a frighteningly high level, the economic recoveries in the US and the UK remain fragile and political and military tensions between China, Japan and South Korea are starting to simmer.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">But overall there is good reason to be optimistic as we look ahead to the coming year. Naturally there have been the usual predictions of a &lsquo;global meltdown&rsquo; in some quarters, but we need to remember that sensational headlines sell newspapers. A continuing gradual recovery isn&rsquo;t going to set anyone&rsquo;s pulse racing.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>So, what assets should you invest in and where in the world?</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>To answer these questions why not join us for coffee on the 11<sup>th</sup> March at the Casa Hotel in Chesterfield?&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>10.00am &nbsp;arrival </strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>10.30am &nbsp;start</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>11.30 finish</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '2014-03-11', '2014-03-11', 'justin_bw_redbraces - Jul 2011.jpg', 'image/pjpeg', 75042, '2014-01-28 11:21:40', '', '2014-01-28 11:21:45', '2014-01-28 11:30:48', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(11, 'The Future of Manufacturing- Breakfast Seminar', 'Group Managing Director of the OSL Group, David Grey MBE is the first key speaker confirmed for this year’s free annual Manufacturing breakfast Seminar.  The event is hosted by Banner Jones Solicitors, Shorts Chartered Accountants, and NatWest and will be held at the Proact Stadium in Chesterfield on Thursday 13 November 2014.\r\n\r\n', '<p>Final details are now confirmed for this year&rsquo;s annual Manufacturing Breakfast Seminar hosted by Shorts Chartered Accountants, NatWest and Banner Jones Solicitors at the Proact Stadium in Chesterfield. This year&rsquo;s event is being held as part of Destination Chesterfield&rsquo;s Made in Chesterfield week on Thursday 13 November 2014. &nbsp;Master Cutler David Grey MBE, Chris Heaton and Dr. Chris Wilson are confirmed as this year&rsquo;s speakers, who will be focusing on the future of manufacturing within the region.</p>\r\n<p>Providing a &rsquo;one stop&rsquo; opportunity to speak with people from many sectors under one roof, representatives from AMRC, Derby University, Manufacturing Advice Service, UKTI, Sheffield EEF, Gallagher Heath, Shorts, NatWest, Banner Jones, Destination Chesterfield and Chesterfield college will also be attending with information stalls.&nbsp; Anyone wanting the opportunity to discuss import / export issues, obtain more information on training or apprenticeships, legal, finance or tax issues relating to Manufacturing businesses will be able to speak to representatives before and after the event.</p>\r\n<p>On site all day, delegates will have the opportunity to look around the AMRC&rsquo;s Mantra bus.&nbsp; Mantra is the Manufacturing Transporter, the AMRC&rsquo;s unique travelling showcase for advanced engineering.&nbsp;&nbsp; A Customised 14m HGV trailer designed to give aspiring young engineers a hands-on experience with real cutting edge technologies.</p>\r\n<p>During the Seminar, Master Cutler, and founder of the OSL Group of Companies, David Grey MBE will be the first speaker. He built his business, by acquisition and organic growth, to a group of six manufacturing companies serving a global market, turning over &pound;35 Million and employing over 400 staff. He was for 3 years a board member of the Sheffield First Partnership, the strategy group for the city. It includes council, private and community sector representation. He was involved in setting up and then latterly served for 3 years as the Chairman of the inward investment agency for the city, Sheffield First for Investment.&nbsp; David has, in his time, been a council member of the Sheffield Chamber of Commerce and Industry, a Director of Business Link and the Chairman of the Business Community Partnership. In 2006, he was asked to lead a bid to win a &pound;26 million grant from Central Government to encourage entrepreneurship in the city. He is now the Chairman of the Local Economy Board charged with monitoring that programme. He was awarded an MBE in the 2010 New Year''s Honours List for his Services to Industry and Regeneration in Sheffield, was recently elected to the Sheffield City Region LEP Board and is currently holding the position of Master Cutler.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The second speaker, Chris Heaton has worked in the professional services and manufacturing sectors at board level in Sheffield, Leeds and London.&nbsp; Chairman of Sheffield Assay Office since 2012 and interim Group Managing Director of OSL Group Limited, Chris is also a previous President of the Sheffield &amp; District Society of Chartered Accountants and has served on the national Institute&rsquo;s Council. He is also well known for his charitable work, and has raised in excess of &pound;70k for Brathay Trust completing endurance challenges: recently completing 30 marathons in 30 days. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The final speaker confirmed is Dr Chris Wilson, a full member of IEMA, Chartered Waste Manager, Chartered Environmentalist, BSI Registered Lead Auditor and Professional Energy Manager. &nbsp;He is a Senior Environment Consultant for Mentor and his key competencies include: energy management/ auditing, environmental legislation and compliance, resource efficiency, renewables, auditing, environmental risk assessment, carbon foot-printing/ management, waste management, climate change, developing and delivering waste/ environmental training and environmental management systems. &nbsp;Chris has published in multiple peer-reviewed journals and won a number of prestigious awards.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Places are offered FREE of charge, but space is limited and early booking is recommended for this event.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">8.00 Registration and breakfast<br />8.30 Presentations begin with Q&amp;A<br />10.30 Close</p>\r\n<h3 style="text-align: left;"><strong>Feedback from previous years </strong></h3>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><em>&ldquo;Very good speakers&rdquo;<strong><br /></strong>&ldquo;Great event&rdquo;</em><br /><em>&ldquo;Interesting and worthwhile&rdquo;</em><br /><em>&ldquo;Extremely interesting presentation&nbsp; &ndash; very relevant&rdquo;</em><br /><em>&ldquo;Good presentations with interesting, current subjects A+++&rdquo;</em><br /><em>&ldquo;Very interesting presentations&rdquo;</em><br /><em>&ldquo;Really good event!&rdquo;</em></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;Book NOW</p>', '2014-11-13', '2014-11-13', 'group shot final.jpg', 'image/pjpeg', 304022, '2014-09-08 13:23:52', '', '2014-09-08 13:18:57', '2014-10-03 14:17:53', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(12, 'Pension and ISA Seminar', 'The new and very varied faces of pensions and Individual Savings Accounts.  In the Autumn statement on the 3rd December 2014 Osborne confirm the ‘new’ pension’s legislation would come into force at the start of the 2015/16 fiscal year, but went further announcing new death benefit proposals for Individual Savings accounts.\r\n\r\nFrom 6th April 2015 ISA accounts left to a spouse or civil partner will of course continue to pass Inheritance Tax free as before - the transfer itself being covered by the spousal exemption. The big difference is that the continuing returns on a deceased partner''s savings will be tax free.\r\n\r\nIf you want to understand how all of these changes might affect you then come along to our free seminar.', '<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Behind these statements is a fundamental shift of emphasis in what a pension and ISA are actually for and how they could be used within a financial plan.&nbsp; Once a pension existed purely to provide an income in later life. But now - under Osborne''s vision - a pension fund could become a new tax-efficient savings vehicle, something that will be particularly attractive within the family&rsquo;s financial plan.</p>\r\n<p>More than that, it will be possible to pass the pension pot on from generation to generation, just like the family silver.</p>\r\n<p>Jillian Thomas Managing Partner of Banner Jones Wealth management commented,</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;In twenty plus years as a Financial Planner I am not sure I have ever seen such fundamental changes, which could dramatically change the ways we save.&nbsp; It is essential for clients to get a broad knowledge of the scope of the changes before the start of the 2015/16 fiscal year, allowing informed decision to be made immediately afterwards&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p>On Thursday 12<sup>th</sup> February 2015 we propose to look at the alterations,</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How these changes affect you?</li>\r\n<li>What these changes mean for your family?</li>\r\n<li>What are the benefits and the pitfalls? </li>\r\n<li>The actions that need to be taken and when?</li>\r\n<li>Does your Will need amending?</li>\r\n<li>What changes will be required in the investment portfolios?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Our speakers are</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Jillian Thomas Partner Banner Jones Wealth Management LLP</li>\r\n<li>David Lane Technical Director of Vestra Wealth</li>\r\n<li>Justin Urquhart Stewart Founder and Head of Corporate Development Seven Investment Management</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Venue:&nbsp; Mosborough Hall Hotel, High Street, Sheffield S20 5EA.</p>\r\n<p>The event starts at 9.30am with coffee and will finish at noon.</p>', '2015-02-12', NULL, 'BJBanner PENSION.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 23902, '2015-01-07 15:11:54', '', '2014-12-04 14:16:14', '2015-01-07 15:11:55', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(13, 'Annual Manufacturing Seminar', 'We are delighted that Richard Carr, Managing Director of the Mechan Group is the first key speaker confirmed for this year’s free annual Manufacturing breakfast Seminar hosted by Banner Jones Solicitors, Shorts Chartered Accountants and NatWest  at the Proact Stadium in Chesterfield on Thursday 26th November 2015.\r\n\r\nOnce again, this event is being  held as part of Destination Chesterfield’s ''Made in Chesterfield'' program, and brings together key speakers from the heart of local business, putting emphasis on the future of manufacturing within the region.  The seminar forms the latest in a program of events by the Manufacturing and Trade Group, sponsored by Banner Jones Solicitors, NatWest and Shorts; further speakers will be announced closer to the event.', '<p>Our first confirmed speakter, Mechan managing director, Richard Carr, joined the Sheffield-based depot maintenance equipment specialists in 2006.&nbsp; Following a management buy-out with three other directors, he set about revolutionising the way Mechan was run, moving the business to modern, new premises in 2009. Since the takeover, export business has become increasingly important to the firm&rsquo;s success and is forecasted to account for 25% of turnover in 2012, compared to just 2% in 2005.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Places are offered free of charge.&nbsp; Space is limited and these events are always well attended; early booking is recommended.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong><br />Date: &nbsp;Thursday 26</strong><strong>th November 2015</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Tim</strong><strong>e: Refreshments fro</strong><strong>m 8</strong><strong>:00am for 8:30am start</strong><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Close: Presentations and Q&amp;A to close at 10:30am</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Location: Proact Stadium,&nbsp;</strong><strong>1866 Sheffield Ro</strong><strong>ad, </strong><strong>C</strong><strong>hesterfield</strong><strong>, Derbyshire S41 8NZ</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><a href="http://www.eventbrite.co.uk/e/annual-manufacturing-seminar-tickets-16655650499" target="_blank">&nbsp;Book your place now</a></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Feedback from previous years</strong></p>\r\n<p><em>&ldquo;Very good speakers&rdquo;<strong><br /></strong>&ldquo;Great event&rdquo;</em><br /><em>&ldquo;Interesting and worthwhile&rdquo;</em><br /><em>&ldquo;Extremely interesting presentation&nbsp; &ndash; very relevant&rdquo;</em><br /><em>&ldquo;Good presentations with interesting, current subjects A+++&rdquo;</em><br /><em>&ldquo;Very interesting presentations&rdquo;</em><br /><em>&ldquo;Really good event!</em></p>', '2015-11-26', '2015-11-26', 'DSC_8667.jpg', 'image/pjpeg', 334404, '2015-05-19 13:27:39', '', '2015-05-19 13:27:43', '2015-05-19 13:35:01', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0);
INSERT INTO `faqs` (`id`, `question`, `answer`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `created_by`, `updated_by`, `recycled`, `recycled_at`, `display`, `position`) VALUES
(1, 'Why do I need a Will? ', '<p>Leaving a Will means you can be sure that everything will be dealt with in the way you would wish following your death. It&rsquo;s a great feeling to know that you won&rsquo;t be leaving your loved ones with a mess to sort out.</p>\r\n<p>If you don&rsquo;t make a Will, the &ldquo;Intestacy Rules&rdquo; will govern how your estate is divided up when you die. They determine which of your relatives receives how much and can lead to some nasty surprises. They don&rsquo;t provide at all for your friends or even for a partner who you may have lived with for years &ndash; they will inherit nothing. Under the Intestacy Rules, your step-children are not counted as your children if you have not formally adopted them and will inherit nothing &ndash; even if their other parents have already died.</p>\r\n<p>When you die, someone will need to deal with the practicalities. If you don&rsquo;t make a Will, you have no control over who this will be and it will usually be a family member.</p>\r\n<p>If you make a Will, you can choose who you would like to deal with things. You may prefer to appoint a professional, such as a solicitor or accountant &ndash; someone who will not be suffering the distress of bereavement.  If you are married and have combined assets of &pound;325,000 or more (for tax year 2009/10), you can also <strong>save up to &pound;130,000 of Inheritance Tax</strong> by having a tax-efficient Will drawn up. That&rsquo;s &pound;130,000 more for your children or your partner to enjoy.</p>', '2011-01-18 17:03:23', '2011-01-18 17:16:24', 1, 1, 0, NULL, 1, 1),
(2, 'Won''t everything just go to my husband/wife?', '<p>Not necessarily. The Intestacy Rules set out a strict order of who will inherit what. If you have children, your spouse may not inherit everything you own, whether or not you are close to your children or how wealthy they are in their own right. Your spouse might not even get the house, depending on how much it is worth.</p>', '2011-01-18 17:17:12', '2011-01-18 17:18:22', 1, 1, 0, NULL, 1, 2),
(3, 'Can I give different people different shares of my estate?', 'Yes. By making a Will, you can set out exactly who is to get what amount. For example, if one of your children needs money more than another, you can leave them unequal amounts if you wish.', '2011-01-18 17:18:15', '2011-01-18 17:18:15', 1, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 3),
(4, 'Can I give money to Charity in my Will?', 'Yes. The Intestacy Rules don&rsquo;t allow for any gifts to charity out of your estate. By making a Will you can leave a set amount or a percentage of your total estate. It&rsquo;s a great way to say &ldquo;thank you&rdquo; for the wonderful work they do &ndash; and it helps to save Inheritance Tax too!', '2011-01-18 17:18:43', '2011-01-18 17:18:43', 1, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 4),
(5, 'Who will see my Will?', 'Your Will is a private document whilst you are alive and becomes a public document after you die and probate is granted. Anyone can then obtain a copy from the Probate Registry for a small fee. While you are alive, though, no one has any right to see your Will unless you want them to.', '2011-01-18 17:19:00', '2011-01-18 17:19:00', 1, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 5),
(6, 'Can the executors and beneficiaries be the same people?', 'Yes. In most cases, there is no reason why the people inheriting your estate can&rsquo;t be the same people as those dealing with the practicalities. We can tell you whether this will cause a problem in your particular circumstances.', '2011-01-18 17:19:17', '2011-01-18 17:19:17', 1, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 6),
(7, 'Does having a Will mean my family won''t need Probate?', 'No. If you have any asset worth over &pound;5,000, any stocks and shares or a property then your executors will usually need to apply for probate. If you don&rsquo;t make a Will, they need to apply for Letters of Administration instead, which is very similar. Unless your assets are all owned jointly with someone else and pass to them automatically, you will need Probate before your estate can be paid out. We can provide detailed advice about this if you need it.', '2011-01-18 17:19:36', '2011-01-18 17:24:36', 1, 1, 0, NULL, 1, 7),
(8, 'I have made a Will with a different firm of solicitors. Can you update it for me or do I have to go back to them?', 'If you bring your existing Will to us, we can offer you a fixed-fee initial meeting to discuss whether it still carries out your wishes or not. If not, we would be happy to update it or to make a new Will. It does not matter who wrote your Will originally.', '2011-01-18 17:19:50', '2011-01-18 17:20:00', 1, 1, 0, NULL, 1, 8),
(9, 'My aunt only has one bank account. Can I deal with this on her behalf?\r\n', '<p>If the bank allows, it is possible for your aunt to name you as a third party on her bank account. This will allow you to withdraw funds and sign cheques on her behalf. We can help your aunt complete the mandate form required to put this in place.</p>', '2011-03-01 11:51:47', '2014-01-15 13:33:33', 2, 1, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(10, 'My aunt receives state benefits. Is it possible for me to collect these on her behalf as well?\r\n', 'It is often possible for you to be named as &ldquo;appointee&rdquo; to receive your aunt&rsquo;s benefits on her behalf. Again, we can help your aunt to complete the forms required for this', '2011-03-01 11:53:27', '2011-03-01 11:54:31', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(11, 'My mother has dementia and would not be able to tell you who she wants to look after her affairs. What can I do?\r\n', '<p>If your mother is not able to make a decision as to who she wishes to look after her affairs herself, and you are willing to take on this role, then we can apply to the Court for Deputyship. This would mean that you would be appointed by the Court to be your mother&rsquo;s Deputy.</p>\r\n<p>We will guide you through the whole process including giving the Court details of your mother&rsquo;s financial situation. As the Court requires we will also notify other members of her family of the application.</p>\r\n<p>Once the Court has all of the information they will consider the application and if they believe that you are suitable to manage your mother&rsquo;s affairs then they will appoint you as her Deputy. You will then be responsible for dealing with all of her finances, under the guidance of the Court.</p>\r\n<p>This means you can pay her bills, provide for her day-to-day needs and take care of any problems that arise. You must keep careful records of everything you do on behalf of your mother and we can help you prepare the annual accounts required by the Court.</p>', '2011-03-01 11:55:11', '2011-03-01 11:56:03', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(12, 'How soon can I file for Divorce?', 'In England you can get divorced if your marriage has broken down irretrivably, usually proved by allegations of adultery or unreasonable behaviour, or if there has been 2 years'' of continously living apart.', '2011-03-22 15:02:29', '2011-03-22 15:52:19', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(13, 'Will we have to go to Court during our divorce?', 'No, getting a divorce should be an administrative excersise only and there are many options open to you that avoid going to Court.', '2011-03-22 15:18:56', '2011-03-22 15:20:10', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(14, 'Will I lose touch with my children?', 'Your aim should be that both parents still play an active part in the raising of the child/children.&nbsp; Usually parents sort this out amongst themselves, although if there are problems mediation can be a good way to resolve this.&nbsp; Going to Court should always be the last resort where children are involved.', '2011-03-22 15:23:19', '2011-03-22 15:23:19', 2, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(15, 'He''s got to keep a roof over our heads hasn''t he?', '<p>Non-residential parents have to pay maintenance for their children; hopefully the amount can be agreed though negotiation and if not then the CSA will decide. Each case is different.&nbsp;&nbsp; If for example the Mum and the children stay in the family home then she may relinquish her claims over any other assets such as pension and savings in return.</p>', '2011-03-22 15:27:14', '2011-03-22 15:27:14', 2, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(16, 'What am I entitled to in a divorce?  Can she take me for every penny?', 'No.&nbsp; Sometimes it may feel as though this has happened. The aim when sharing out matrimonial assets is to be fair.&nbsp; Both spouses have to make full disclosure about their assets and debts before any decisions can be made about distribution, trying to hide anything won''t work.&nbsp; Factors which are important when sharing out the assets include the current and future needs of each spouse and any dependent children; the length of marriage and the age, earning capacity and contributions of each party.', '2011-03-22 15:31:20', '2011-03-22 15:53:19', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(17, 'What about my pension?', '<p>Pensions are a matrimonial asset and almost certainly (depending on the respective ages and the length of the marriage) your spouse will be able to claim some of it.&nbsp; If you have a very good pension you may decide to give up your interest in other assets (e.g. house and savings) so that your pension stays untouched.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '2011-03-22 15:34:34', '2011-03-22 15:34:34', 2, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(18, 'We''ve sorted it ourselves, it''s binding isn''t it?', 'Almost certainly not.&nbsp; For an agreement to be legally binding there must have been full financial disclosure,&nbsp; independent legal advice and an order made by the Court.', '2011-03-22 15:36:41', '2011-03-22 15:36:41', 2, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(19, 'I''ve heard using a solicitor can be expensive?', 'Can you afford not to have one?&nbsp; Yes, Divorce can be expensive, but without sound legal advice to help you negotiate the pitfalls and help you achieve a fair outcome it can be even more so.', '2011-03-22 15:39:42', '2011-03-22 15:39:42', 2, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(20, 'How long will it take before I get compensated ?\r\n', '<p>In most cases, the limiting factor is the length of time which has to pass before a final opinion can be obtained from a medical expert as to the extent to which an injured person has effected a recovery. In the simplest of cases a conclusion may be reached in around 6 months. However, where more severe injuries are sustained then it may take a number of years to get to a point where the medical eveidence is sufficiently clear to enable the case to be concluded.</p>\r\n<p>In cases where liability is admitted but the case cannot be concluded quickly because of the nature of the injuries then it may be possible to obtain an interrim payment on account of the final award of compensation to be paid.</p>', '2011-03-22 15:55:15', '2011-03-22 18:18:25', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(21, 'How much will I get ?\r\n', '<p>The amount of compensation to be received is determined by an assessment of the extent to whichyou have been&nbsp;injured and have effected a recovery from those injuries. Each case is considered in the light of other cases which have been dealt with by the Courts so as to reach an appropriate level of award.</p>\r\n<p>In addition to the award for the injuries sustained you can also claim for other financial loss such as lost earnings, travelling expenses and the cost of medication.Further and where appropriate a claim can be made for the value or cost of care required or the loss of benefits such as a pension.</p>', '2011-03-22 15:55:30', '2011-03-22 19:22:17', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(22, 'Will I have to go to court ?\r\n', 'It is rare that a claim will proceed to a final hearing before the Court which&nbsp;you would have&nbsp;to attend.', '2011-03-22 15:55:48', '2011-03-22 19:23:22', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(23, 'Will I have to visit a Doctor as part of the case ?\r\n', 'In all cases where a claim for personal injuries is made , that claim needs to be supported with medical evidence in the form of a medical report. This report is prepared following a medical examination with a nominated medical expert which will be arranged by your Solicitor.', '2011-03-22 15:56:04', '2011-03-22 18:26:43', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(24, 'What happens if I lose the case ?\r\n', '<p>There are many different answers to this question which will depend on the exact terms of your retainer with your Solicitor.&nbsp;The answer below should only be taken as general guidance and you should ensure that your Solicitor makes the implications of losing the case clear to you given the manner in which you choose to fund your case.</p>\r\n<p>If you lose the case then your liability for legal costs will depend on a number of factors and in particular the manner in which the claim is being funded at the point which the claim has reached.</p>\r\n<p>In most cases where a claim is lost or discontinued prior to the issue of court proceddings then no costs will generally be recovered by the successful opponent from you.</p>\r\n<p>Where a case is unsuccessful after court proceedings are issued then it is likely that you would be held responsible for your opponents costs . Where&nbsp;you have &nbsp;the benefit of a policy of legal expenses insurance then it is likely that your opponents costs will be covered by that policy. Where no such policy is in place then it is likely that you will be responsible personally for those costs.</p>\r\n<p>Where a case is unsuccessful after court proceedings are issued then&nbsp;you will generally also be responsible for your own legal costs. Where the claim is being pursued on a conditional fee agreement then no charge will be made by the&nbsp;your Solicitor. However, in all other casesyou will be reponsible for your own costs save where a policy of legal expenses insurance is in place which covers those costs.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '2011-03-22 15:56:25', '2011-03-22 18:54:41', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(26, 'What happens if I have Legal expenses Insurance ?\r\n', '<p>If you have legal expenses insurance then we will contact your legal expenses insurers to seek authority to represent you under that policy.</p>\r\n<p>Where we represent you under a policy of legal expenses insurance then in most cases&nbsp;from the date when cover is confirmed and up to the maximum cover provided by the policy your own and any of your opponents&nbsp;legal costs ordered to be paid by you will be met by your insurers.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '2011-03-22 15:56:56', '2011-03-22 19:09:10', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(27, 'If I dont have legal Expenses Insurance can I get it ?\r\n', 'In most case where we represent a Claimant under a conditional fee agreement we will advise in relation to the obtaining of a policy of after the event legal expenses insurance and if appropriate we will make an application for such cover.', '2011-03-22 15:57:12', '2011-03-22 19:11:10', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
(28, 'How will I fund my case ?\r\n', '<p>We will before an action is taken&nbsp;advise on the possible methods of funding a case.</p>\r\n<p>We will advise on :</p>\r\n<p>-Private fee agreements</p>\r\n<p>-Conditional Fee agreements</p>\r\n<p>-Legal expenses insurance</p>\r\n<p>-Legal Aid</p>\r\n<p>-Trade Union funding</p>\r\n<p>Following our advice we will then pursue your case based upon your chosen method of funding.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '2011-03-22 15:57:28', '2011-03-22 19:20:33', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0),
