(13, 'Jargon Buster', 'jargon_buster', 'Jargon Buster', 13, 0, 0, 1, '2010-04-29 08:55:42', '<h2 class="shape">Please scroll down for an A-Z&nbsp;glossary of legal terms including:</h2>\r\n<p class="shape">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div class="shape">1. Residential Property</div>\r\n<div class="shape">2. Family Law</div>\r\n<div class="shape">3. Personal Injury</div>\r\n<div class="shape">4. Employment Law</div>\r\n<div class="shape">5. Wills &amp; Probate</div>\r\n<p class="shape">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2 class="shape">1. Residential Property</h2>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<table class="TableStyle1" border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Absolute title</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>See title absolute</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Abstract of title</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>A summary of the documents and facts showing ownership - used to prove title in cases when title is unregistered</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Appurtenant</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Belonging</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Assignment</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>This ia a&nbsp;disposal or transfer of property.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;It is most commonly used in relation to the transfer of the benefit of a lease, which will be accomplished by a deed called ''an assignment''</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Beneficial owner</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Land ownership where the person is entitled to it for his/her own benefit</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Chancel repair liability</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>If a property is located within the boundaries of a tithe district (a sub-division of an historical parish) there is a continuing potential to charge for chancel repairs it may be subject to Chancel Repair Liability. We can insure you against this</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Charge</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>A liability burdening land securing the payment of money e.g.&nbsp;a mortgage charge</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Commonhold</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>This is an alternative way to&nbsp;own flats&nbsp;and other interdependent properties under a lease. It is not a new estate in land but a new form of freehold ownership - see freehold</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Consideration</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>The amount of cash (or monies worth) of a transaction</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Contract</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>A legal agreement between parties</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Conveyance</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>This document is now referred to as a transfer but historically it was a document effecting the transfer of property from the vendor to the purchaser.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Counterpart</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>It is common for a lease to be prepared in counterpart. The part, or copy, signed by the person granting the lease is called the ''original'', and the part signed by the tenant is called the ''counterpart''</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Covenant</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>A promise given by a deed</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Deed</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Written or printed instrument (i.e. a document) effecting legal disposition.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Easement</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>A right owned by one landowner over the land of another, e.g. a right of way</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Estate</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>This can have dual meaning:</p>\r\n<p>(1) in land - the extent of a person''s ownership<br />(2) the estate of a deceased person - all the property owned by that person at their death</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Execute</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>The signing of a document</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Floating charge</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>A charge on all assets of a company which does not affect the company''s power of disposal unless and until the charge becomes payable</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Freehold</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Tenure (possession) by which land is held</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Ground rent</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>This is another term used for ''rent''</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Joint tenants</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Co-owners of land - when one of them dies, his/her rights of ownership pass to the survivor(this contrasts with&nbsp;tenants in common)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Joint and several</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Together as one, and also separately, e.g. of liability under a covenant</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Leasehold</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Land (or property) held under a lease</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Lease</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>A contract by which a lessor, usually&nbsp;for rent, leases land and/or buildings to a lessee</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Term of a lease</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>This is the length of the lease which is usually measured in years</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Legal charge</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>A mortgage</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Lessee</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Holder of or tenant of a lease</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Lessor</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Person who grants a lease to a lessee</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Local search</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Local Authority search&nbsp;( i.e. council )</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Mortgage</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>To give a lender&nbsp;important rights over property, including the power of sale, as security for&nbsp;the loan</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;NPV</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Net Present Value which is a formula applied to the term of a lease, the annual rental and a discounting constant</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Official copies</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>A term referring to physical hard paper copies of Land Register entries produced by the Land Registry thus being ''Official Copies'' (as opposed to copies being obtained via the internet for example)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Overriding interest</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>The rights of a person in actual occupation of the land e.g. they have an overriding interest</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Particulars of sale</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>This is normally prepared by an Estate Agent and comprises of the descriprion of the property to be sold and the terms and conditions on which the sale is to take place</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Power of attorney</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Authority given by one person to another (the attorney) to act for him/her (e.g. to execute a deed) in his/her absence</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Private treaty</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>A sale not by auction</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Purchaser</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>The person or body buying a property/lease</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Register</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>The&nbsp;HM Land Registry records property ownership throughout England and Wales on a register</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Registered title</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>The Register holds the official record of ownership, covenants and charges</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Rent</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>A periodic payment in respect of land, e.g.<br />ground rent - the sum payable under a lease or a rent charge - rent payable in respect of freehold property</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Restrictive covenant</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>A promise under seal restricting the use of land - see covenant. This can restrict the purchaser from various developments on the property and these should be checked over before exhange</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Root of title</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>A&nbsp;vendor''s ownership is traced vis this document</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;SDLT</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Stamp Duty Land Tax. A lengthy form (an SDLT1) describing the details of a property transaction. This is&nbsp;normally filled out by a Solicitor acting as an agent for the purchaser which accompanies the payment of stamp duty to the Inland Revenue</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Searches</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Enquiries usually made, usually made by a purchaser''s Solicitor to find out what incumbrances affect a property</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Subject to contract</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>When an offer is made ''subject to contract'' this means that either party is at liberty to decide not to go ahead with the transaction</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Tenancy</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>The temporary possession or holding by a tenant of land or property owned by another</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Tenant</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Person or body&nbsp;who occupies land or building under a lease</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Tenants in common</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Where two or more people are entitled to the proceeds of sale in land in distinct shares. On the death of one, his/her interest will not pass to the survivor(s) but will become part of their estate</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Tenure</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>The terms on which land is held e.g. freehold or leasehold</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Title absolute</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>The highest quality of ownership in land recognised by the system of registration of title</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Title</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>The evidence of a person''s right to land</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Transfer</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>The name for the conveyance, also known as a the TR1 document describes various details about the transaction</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Transferee</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Body to whom a transfer is made</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Transferor</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Body making the transfer</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Trust for sale</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>A trust which requires the trustees to sell the property. Co-owners of land will hold it as joint tenants on trust for sale perhaps for the benefit of themselves</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Trust</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>Where property is transferred to a person on the understanding that they&nbsp;will apply it&nbsp;to a&nbsp;particular purpose</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Unregistered title</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>A person proves his/her ownership by producing deeds as it&nbsp;will not be on the land registry register.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Vacant possesion</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>A term used to describe property being sold free from any leases or tenancies, usually an empty property</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Vendor</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>The person or body selling a property/lease</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="34%" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Will</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="65%" valign="top">\r\n<p>A legal document stating the&nbsp;person''s wishes regarding the disposal of his/her property after his/her death</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<h2>2.&nbsp;Family Law</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;&nbsp;Coming soon</h2>\r\n<h2>3. Personal Injury</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<table border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Claimant</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>The person making the Claim</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Claim Form</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>A formal document used to issue Court Proceedings against the at-fault third party</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Contributory Negligence</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>A portion of blame that may be alleged against you for partly causing the accident.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Damages</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>The compensation you may be entitled to receive</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Evidence</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>This is what is required to prove any aspect of your personal claim, such as a medical report to prove your injuries</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Excess</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>The amount you must&nbsp;pay towards the cost of repairs to your vehicle if you are insured under a comprehensive policy. This is generally recoverable from the at-fault third party.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Insured Losses</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>Losses that are covered by your insurance policy</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Legal Expense Cover</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>This covers losses that are not covered by your standard insurance policy,&nbsp;including personal injury.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Limitation Deadline</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>You have three years (if you are over 18) from the date of the accident to negotiate the settlement of a claimor issue a claim form in either the County Court or High Court. If you are under 18 at the time of the accident, you have until you are&nbsp;21</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Litigation</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>The name of the legal process once you have issued a Claim form at Court.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Negligence</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>You must be able to prove the other party owed you a duty of care, was in breach of that duty, and that the breach caused your injury or damage. The injury or loss must also be&nbsp;a consequence of the breach. Even if the other party was only partly to blame, you may still be entitled to compensation</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Third Party</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>This is the person you are claiming against. If you issue a Claim form they&nbsp;then become known as the Defendant.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Uninsured Losses</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>These are losses that are not covered by your insurance policy. These can include personal injury, excess and loss of earnings</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<h2>4. Employment Law</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<table border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>ACAS</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>The Advisory Conciliation and Arbitration Service is a Government-funded public agency providing a conciliation and mediation service.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Annual Leave</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>This is another phrase for your holiday entitlement. As an employee or a worker, if you work a five-day week, you are entitled to a minimum of 28 days per year including bank holidays.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Appeal</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>You can appeal against your dismissal if you have been dismissed otherwise this could affect the amount of compensation you receive if your claim is successful</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Discrimination</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>This can be direct and indirect.&nbsp; Direct discrimination is less favourable treatment on one or more of the prohibited grounds (race, sex, disability, age, sexual orientation or religious belief). Indirect discrimination occurs for example when your employer applies a provision or practice to all its staff, but that provision or practice disproportionately impacts upon persons of a specific race including yourself.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Employment Tribunal</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>Employment issues are heard in a court of law called a tribunal</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>ET1</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>A claim form used to lodge your claim with the employment Tribunal.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>ET3</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>Your employer&rsquo;s defence to your claim. The employer has 28 days from receipt of the ET1 (sent to them by the Employment Tribunal) to respond to your claim</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Grievance</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>A letter to your employer detailing the matters you are complaining of (such as unlawful deduction of wages or a discriminatory act).</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Mitigating your Loss</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>If you are dismissed, you will need to satisfy the Employment Tribunal that you have made all reasonable attempts to find alternative work.&nbsp; This includes things like keeping a record of all job applications, any visits to the job centre and if you join an employment agency, a record of the initial appointment and any subsequent job offers</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>National Minimum Wage</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>The minimum amount your employer is obliged to pay you per hour</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Notice Pay</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>You are usually entitled to receive notice pay if your employer terminates your contract. The minimum period of notice after one month of service is one week for each complete year of service, to a maximum of 12 weeks for 12 years of service.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Respondent</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>This is usually your employer or the person who will respond to your claim. If it is a complaint of discrimination, this can also be a named individual who would normally be the alleged perpetrator of the discrimination.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Unlawful deduction from wages</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>If your employer holds back your pay for no reason, you may be able to bring a claim. You would first need to raise a grievance with your employer setting out your complaint</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<h2>5. Wills &amp; Probate</h2>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<table border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Administrator</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>The administrator is the person entitled to manage and settle the deceased''s affairs when there is no will in place. The Rules of Intestacy dictate who the&nbsp;administrators can be</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Affidavit</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>A statement in writing made upon oath</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Assets</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>Assets are anything you own which has value; such as&nbsp;land, property, cash,&nbsp;savings and investments, cars and&nbsp;family heirlooms</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Beneficiary</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>Someone who is named in the Will to receive inheritance from&nbsp;the estate.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Bequeath</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>This is to leave money or property to a beneficiary named in a Will.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Bequest</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>A gift of money or property in a Will.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Chattels</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>These are any personal belongings including cars, jewellery, collections and&nbsp;household items such as antiques and furntiure&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Civil partner</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>Someone with whom you have registered a same sex Civil Partnership with under the Civil Partnership Act 2004</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Codicil</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>This is a legal document which can be used to make minor changes to a Will. To be valid the same formalities have to be adhered to as a Will.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Crown</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>Crown&nbsp;is another term for the government.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Estate</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>Your estate includes your home, car,&nbsp;bank accounts, investments and anything else you owned in your sole name such as jewellery. Anything you owned jointly will automatically pass to the surviving joint owner when you die.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Executor<br /><br /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>An Executor is the person or people named in a Will to manage and administer an estate</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Grant of Probate<br /><br /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>This is the legal document issued to the Executors by the Probate Registry, granting them the legal authority to deal with a deceased''s estate.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Guardian</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>The people nominated in a Will to look after any children under the age of 18 in the event of their parent''s death.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Inheritance Tax (IHT).</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>The tax payable on an estate when someone dies. Everyone has an Inheritance Tax free allowance called the&nbsp;''nil rate band''.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Intestate</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>This is the term used when someone dies without a valid Will in place. They die Intestate.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Issue</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>''Issue'' are the children, grandchildren and remoter descendents of a person, whether born within or outside marriage, including adopted children.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>&nbsp;Joint tenancy</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>This is a form of property ownership where all the joint owners own the property together. On the death of one owner, their interest passes to the remaining owner(s) by survivorship.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Letters of Administration</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>This is the legal document issued by the Probate Registry to the administrator of an estate of a person who has died Intestate</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Life interest</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>A gift that gives someone the right to&nbsp;any income generated from an asset or the right to occupation of a property for the duration of their life</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Pecuniary gifts</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>These are gifts of a specific sum of money</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Residuary Beneficiary</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>Someone nominated in a Will to receive the remainder or residual part of a deceased''s estate after all other Beneficiaries have received their inheritance and all debts have been paid</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Residue<br /><br /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>This is the part of an estate which is left after the payment of all debts, funeral expenses, Inheritance, Income and Capital Gains&nbsp;Tax and specific and pecuniary gifts are paid.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Specific gifts</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>These are specific gifts which are either of financial or sentimental value.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Rules of Intestacy<br /><br /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>When someone dies without a Will (see Intestate), strict inheritance laws called the Rules of Intestacy apply. These rules determine who administers and who will inherit from the deceased''s estate (see estate) and in what proportions.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Spouse</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>A spouse is a married partner (not a cohabitee).</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Substitute beneficiary</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>This is a person who is named as an alternative beneficiary in case another beneficiary&nbsp;predeceases the person making the Will.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Survivorship</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>When&nbsp;someone dies any jointly held assets, including property and savings passes automatically to the surviving joint owner by survivorship.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Tenants in Common</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>This is a form of property ownership where each joint tenant owns a separate share&nbsp;of the property. On the death of one of the part owners, their share passes to the Beneficiaries&nbsp;in line with the&nbsp;Will or the Rules of Intestacy</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Testator (or Testatrix, if female)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>This is the person who is writing the Will.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Trust</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>A legal arrangement where one or more people (Trustees) are made legally responsible for assets which are placed in the Trust for the benefit of the named&nbsp;Beneficiaries</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Trustee</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>A Trustee is the person responsible for administering a Trust. This involves looking after property and/or assets for the benefit of the named Beneficiaries. Trustees have a duty to act in good faith, which means they cannot enrich themselves at the expense of their Beneficiaries. Solicitors make good independent trustees for that reason.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Will</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>A Will is a legal document declaring their intention as to what they would like to happen to their estate after their death.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="199" valign="top">\r\n<p>Witness</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width="369" valign="top">\r\n<p>A witness is someone who verifies the signing of a Will. A Will must have two witnesses who verify the signature of the testator. They must sign the Will in the presence of each other for the will to be valid and the testator and must not benefit from the Will.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>', '2010-11-12 17:05:26', '2014-10-02 14:15:53', '', '', 1, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0, '<p>Don''t keep quiet about our great service</p>\r\n<p>We''d love to add you to our list of testimonials</p>\r\n<p>Write to us now</p>', '104_iStock_000012897655XSmall.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 75121, '2011-03-22 16:35:09', '', 'family_highlight', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, NULL, ''),
(14, 'Useful Links', 'useful_links', 'Useful Links', 14, 0, 0, 1, '2010-04-29 08:55:42', '<p><a href="http://www.rememberacharity.org.uk/">www.rememberacharity.org.uk</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.wphcc.org.uk/legacy">www.wphcc.org.uk/legacy</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.campbell-co.co.uk">www.campbell-co.co.uk</a><br />Campbell &amp; Co are an independent Sheffield based commercial and industrial property consultancy, having been established in the city for over 13years.</p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.adviceguide.org.uk/index/your_rights/legal_system.htm">www.adviceguide.org.uk/index/your_rights/legal_system.htm</a><br />Information on: courts of law; using a solicitor; help with legal costs; small claims; personal injuries; alternatives to court; police powers; issues affecting prisoners.</p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.ageconcernchesterfield.org.uk">www.ageconcernchesterfield.org.uk</a><br />We&nbsp;&nbsp;hold a Legal Advice Clinic at Chesterfield Age Concern every Tuesday 10-11am.</p>\r\n<p><span style="font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 15px; font-weight: bold;"> </span></p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<h2>Useful Wealth Management links</h2>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.autoenrolment.co.uk/additional-pensions-income-calculator" target="_blank">www.autoenrolment.co.uk/additional-pensions-income-calculator</a></p>\r\n<p>A simple tool that will display roughly how much extra you can expect in retirement per month if you increase pension contributions.</p>\r\n<p><a href="http://lifehacker.com/5814716/ten-tools-that-do-the-retirement-planning-for-you" target="_blank">lifehacker.com/5814716/ten-tools-that-do-the-retirement-planning-for-you<br /></a>A step by step guide to painlessly plan and vet your retirement.</p>', '2010-11-12 17:05:46', '2015-09-08 14:30:07', '', '', 1, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0, '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 'family_highlight', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, NULL, ''),
(15, 'About Us', 'about_us', 'About Us - Solicitors in Sheffield & Chesterfield.', 15, 0, 0, 1, '2010-04-29 08:55:42', '<h2>Banner Jones&nbsp;Solicitors is an award winning law firm with offices in Chesterfield, Sheffield, Dronfield and Mansfield.&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<p>We are committed (and have been for over 130 years) to providing our clients with no-nonsense legal advice tailored to your individual needs and circumstances.</p>\r\n<p>We have specialist departments offering high quality advice across the full spectrum of legal services, including personal matters such as Personal Injury, Divorce, Crime, Wills and Probate, Residential Property and Dispute Resolution through to business advice on Company Formation, Commercial Property, Company Finance, Partnership Agreements, Debt Recovery and Employment issues. We also have a Notary Public in our team. He is&nbsp;one of the few remaining Notaries in Chesterfield.</p>\r\n<p>On the 1st September 2013 Banner Jones Solicitors merged with local firm Bilton Hammond Solicitors. Banner Jones Solicitors and Bilton Hammond Solicitors are trading names of Banner Jones Ltd.<br />In Chesterfield we trade as Banner Jones Solicitors, and in Mansfield we trade as Bilton Hammond Solicitors.</p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../page/why-choose-banner-jones">Why choose Banner Jones?</a></p>\r\n<p><strong><strong>To make an inquiry, or to arrange an appointment, telephone</strong>&nbsp;<strong><span class="calltracks_bannerjonescouk-main">0330 017 6309</span>*&nbsp;</strong>or email&nbsp;<a href="mailto:info@bannerjones.co.uk">info@bannerjones.co.uk</a>.</strong></p>\r\n<p>*<strong><sub>calls cost no more than a local 01 number and are included in your mobile minutes.</sub></strong></p>', '2010-11-12 17:06:42', '2015-04-29 14:43:16', 'Banner Jones is an award winning law firm with office in Chesterfield, Sheffield and Dronfield. Get legal advice tailored to your needs.', '', 1, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0, '<p>We are a leading firm in the Legal 500</p>', '359_UK_leading_firm_2014.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 7199, '2015-01-05 11:14:00', '', 'family_highlight', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '/page/why-choose-banner-jones', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, NULL, ''),
(16, 'History', 'history', 'History', 16, 0, 0, 1, '2010-04-29 08:55:42', '<p style="text-align: justify;">Although Banner Jones is now a diverse, progressive and forward thinking Law firm we have humble beginnings dating back over 130 years.</p>\r\n<h2 style="text-align: justify;">Key Dates In Our History</h2>\r\n<h2 style="text-align: justify;">1878</h2>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Solicitor William Tom Jones and his junior partner John Middleton occupied 28 Glumangate</p>\r\n<h2 style="text-align: justify;">1890</h2>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Jones &amp; Middleton Solicitors bought 24 Glumangate.&nbsp; W.T. Jones concentrated on the conveyancing work, whilst John Middleton on the other hand specialised in advocacy, becoming particularly concerned with agricultural cases. Jones &amp; Middleton traded for a staggering 109 years before merging with Banners Solicitors to form Banner Jones Middleton in 1999.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Banner Jones is now the&nbsp;oldest business on Glumangate.</p>\r\n<h2 style="text-align: justify;">1984<span style="font-size: small;"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"><span style="color: #000000;">&nbsp;</span></span></span></h2>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Banners had its origins at&nbsp; Marsden Chambers on Saltergate where two of the firm&rsquo;s present Directors, Robert&nbsp;Banner and Peter Jones were in partnership with another local Solicitor, Colin Eagle. The firm was then&nbsp; known as Eagle Banner and Jones. <strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n&nbsp;In 1984 the partnership of Eagle, Banner and Jones dissolved and a new partnership was formed when John Hawkins joined Robert Banner and Peter Jones to form the partnership of Banner Jones &amp; Hawkins. Banner Jones Hawkins grew with branches opening in Stavely, Clay Cross and Dronfield\r\n<h2 style="text-align: justify;">1993</h2>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">On the 1st May 1993&nbsp; Banner Jones &amp; Hawkins become known as&nbsp;Banners Solicitors.</p>\r\n<h2 style="text-align: justify;">1999</h2>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">1st September 1999 the firm of Banners merged with Jones &amp; Middleton to create Banner Jones Middleton. A considerable advantage was gained by the natural fit of the two businesses which complimented each other and allowed for increased specialism going forwards.</p>\r\n<h2 style="text-align: justify;">2007</h2>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Banner Jones Middleton on the 1st June 2007 merged with local firm Glossops. Glossops Solicitors dated back to 1885 when two brothers formed the practice formerly named W &amp; A Glossop. &nbsp;The Glossops name is still incorporated within the brand in Chesterfield as &lsquo;Banner Jones with Glossops&rsquo;.</p>\r\n<h2 style="text-align: justify;">2007</h2>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Banner Jones Middleton was rebranded Banner Jones Solicitors on the 1st October 2007 following the acquisition of Cotton &amp; Co in Sheffield.&nbsp;&nbsp; Hugh Cotton who soon after retired from the business leaves behind him a successful growing business which still carries his name today &ldquo;Banner Jones with Cotton &amp; Co&rdquo; in Sheffield.</p>\r\n<h2 style="text-align: justify;">2008</h2>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">In 2008 Banner Jones Solicitors incorporated into a Limited company known as Banner Jones Ltd.&nbsp; The &nbsp;trading name is still&nbsp;Banner Jones Solicitors.</p>\r\n<h2 style="text-align: justify;">2010</h2>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">On the 1st December 2010 Banner Jones Ltd acquired Robert L Bashforth &amp; Co.&nbsp; Robert Bashforth had been a sole practioner in Chesterfield for 12 years and now works within Banner Jones.</p>\r\n<h2 style="text-align: justify;">2013</h2>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><br />On the 1st Septemer 2013 Banner Jones merged with Bilton Hammond Solicitors.&nbsp; Both Banner Jones and Bilton Hammond are trading names of Banner Jones Ltd.</p>', '2010-11-12 17:06:56', '2014-10-23 10:01:02', '', '', 1, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0, 'William Jones 1890', '16_william_jones.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 13377, '2011-03-04 16:02:47', '', 'family_highlight', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, NULL, ''),
(17, 'Awards', 'awards', 'Awards', 17, 0, 0, 1, '2010-04-29 08:55:42', '<h3 style="text-align: left;">Derbyshire Times Business Awards:&nbsp; Excellence in Professional Services 2013</h3>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">On November 21st 2013 Banner Jones Solcitors were awarded winner of the Excellence in Professional Services category.&nbsp; Judges were impressed by our outstanding contribution to the sector and our commitment to customer service.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><img src="../../..//assets/page_contents/17/contained_images/8d551cd013ad_14_DT Business Awards 2009.JPG?1296146247" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" width="144" height="123" /><img src="../../..//assets/page_contents/17/contained_images/0e1d0ebf57af_235_on stage.jpg?1389621705" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" width="182" height="125" /></p>\r\n<h3 style="text-align: left;">Legal 500 ''Leading Firm'' 2013 - Family Law Team</h3>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">On the 25th September Banner Jones were ranked in the UK''s Legal 500 for the first time.&nbsp;&nbsp; The award came following a detailed submission to the publisher who deemed us worthy of a position in the East Midlands, Private Client category for our services to Family Law.&nbsp;&nbsp; The Solicitor and Director who heads up our Family team, Helena Downing has also been given the accolade of ''Recommended Lawyer'' in the rankings.&nbsp; Banner Jones have the largest and most experienced Family Law team in the area and are delighted to have received this recognition for the work we do.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"><img src="../../../assets/page_contents/17/contained_images/dc79bcd185f2_218_UK_leading_firm_2013legal 500.jpg?1380277468" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" width="109" height="128" /></p>\r\n<h3 style="text-align: left;">Derbyshire''s Best ''Excellence in Customer Service'' 2011</h3>\r\n<p>We&nbsp;were recently selected as finalists in the 2011 Derbyshire Chamber of Commerce, Excellence in Customer Service award.&nbsp; Simon Wright, Executive Director says &ldquo;In an ongoing satisfaction survey 96% of our clients said that they would recommend us to a friend. We are very proud of this statistic as it highlights how importantly we take customer service. At Banner Jones our clients are our lifeblood and we are constantly striving to give them the very best in customer service"</p>\r\n<p><img src="../../../assets/page_contents/17/contained_images/9b85236e3974_130_DNCC email signatures finalist Derby.jpg?1319635690" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" width="176" height="104" />&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src="../../../assets/page_contents/17/contained_images/cba2b137231c_131_team at.JPG?1319635829" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" width="202" height="111" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3><strong>INTL Magazine ''Trusts &amp; Estates Law Firm of the Year UK'' 2011</strong></h3>\r\n<p>We have been chosen as the Trusts &amp; Estates Law Firm of the Year for 2011 by the readers of this international magazine for our commitment to this&nbsp;area of law.</p>\r\n<p><strong><img src="../../../assets/page_contents/17/contained_images/3647a88edb3e_129_Global 2011 Awards Winner.JPG?1316001723" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" width="163" height="122" /></strong></p>\r\n<h3><strong>&nbsp;</strong><strong>ICFM Highly Commended Top Tier Firm-</strong><strong>&nbsp;''Business Legal Services'' 2011</strong></h3>\r\n<p>We have been awarded the HIGHLY COMMENDED &ndash; TOP TIER FIRM status in the TOP BUSINESS LEGAL SERVICES FIRM OF THE YEAR &ndash; UK category.&nbsp; These awards are voted for by the readers of the InterContinental Finance Magazine&nbsp;who said that Banner Jones is considered to have performed to exceptional levels during one of the most difficult economic periods ever experienced.</p>\r\n<p><img src="../../../assets/page_contents/17/contained_images/16fc89883918_120_ICFM.bmp?1307350040" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" width="137" height="136" /></p>\r\n<h3><strong>Derbyshire Times Business Awards, ''Customer Service Award'' 2010</strong></h3>\r\n<p>Judges comment: &ldquo;We''re impressed by their commitment to providing excellent service and the in-depth and rigorous checks and training they&rsquo;ve introduced.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p><img src="../../../assets/page_contents/17/contained_images/49932eb90c38_14_DT Business Awards 2009.JPG?1296146247" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" width="149" height="93" />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src="../../../assets/page_contents/17/contained_images/09791890ca18_36_team.JPG?1298648443" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" width="172" height="93" /></p>\r\n<h3><strong>Derbyshire Times Business Awards,&nbsp; ''Team of the Year'' 2009</strong></h3>\r\n<p>Judges comment: &ldquo;This business has adapted to the modern world and exploited new opportunities where the more traditional markets have dwindled. This is a business where team work is leading to innovation.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<img src="../../../assets/page_contents/17/contained_images/49932eb90c38_14_DT Business Awards 2009.JPG?1296146247" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" width="150" height="99" />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3><strong>ACQ finance magazine &lsquo;Regional Law Firm of the Year&rsquo; 2009</strong></h3>\r\n<p>ACQ Finance Magazine is a leading corporate finance publication which undertakes an independent poll of industry peers, who were encouraged to vote on those deals and subjects that they think stood out from the crowd in the last 12 months.</p>\r\n<p><img src="../../../assets/page_contents/17/contained_images/05c8e380ebdc_15_ACQ-Country-Awards-2009.png?1296146263" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" width="204" height="50" /></p>', '2010-11-12 17:07:13', '2014-01-13 14:02:53', '', '', 1, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0, 'If you''d like to make an appointment to see an award winning solicitor - call us today', '92_iStock_000009311779XSmall.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 112950, '2011-09-14 15:00:59', '', 'family_highlight', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '/web/contact_us', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL);
