(183, 'Wealth Management Services', 'wealth_management_services', 'Wealth Management Services', 177, 0, 0, 1, '2010-04-29 08:55:42', '<h2 style="text-align: justify;">Our Services</h2>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Banner Jones Wealth Management can help you to grow and&nbsp;protect your wealth and advise you on how best to&nbsp;plan for&nbsp;sharing it&nbsp;in the future.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>Advice to Trustees</strong></p>\r\nThe Trustee Act 2000 imposes specific duties on Trustees. These include the implementation of a standard investment criteria, regular revision of the suitability of the chosen investment strategy, and commensurately, estate planning requires the need for diversification through differing types of investments held. We offer access to advice to Trustees on the suitability of different asset classes and investment risk as well as on the most tax-efficient investment products, to meet the Trust&rsquo;s objectives.<br /><br /><strong>Estate Planning</strong>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Much can be achieved by careful planning and drafting of Wills, and the ability to transfer the unused portion of a nil rate band between spouses or civil partners. This has greatly improved the Inheritance Tax position for many people. However, for those with larger estates, alternative planning solutions are still required and we are experienced in advising on some less widely known opportunities to reduce the impact of IHT.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>Equity Release</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">We are all living longer&nbsp;which&nbsp;means that we may need to consider alternative ways to fund our retirement.&nbsp; Equity Release is an option where you can continue to live in your house,&nbsp;&nbsp;using the equity&nbsp;that is tied up in your home to provide you with a lump sum<strong>.&nbsp; </strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>Care Home Fees</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">As we grow older and require more care, we are entering one of the most emotional and daunting period of our lives. Despite this, very few people seek professional advice on what is probably one of the largest financial commitments they have ever made - paying for care home fees.&nbsp; Whether you are being funded by the State or paying privately for your care, there is much to consider. Choosing the right type of care requires considerable research and consideration and we can help you make the right decision based on your circumstances.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>Estate Protection</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">We see<strong> </strong>Life Assurance as a last resort, but its use in conjunction with the right Trust arrangements can be a powerful planning tool in preserving hard-earned assets for the next generation for a fraction of the cost of the IHT bill. We have access to many years&rsquo; experience in advising on the most suitable type of policies to provide you and your clients with the reassurance that the provision they take out will perform the task that they want it to.<br /><br /><strong>Wealth Management</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">For professionals and business owners alike, it is beneficial to assess whether&nbsp;your financial strategy is likely to meet&nbsp;with your&nbsp;personal aims and objectives and provide&nbsp;you with&nbsp;your desired lifestyle in retirement.</p>\r\n<p><span style="color: #000000;">We offer a comprehensive financial plan; this includes a valuable lifetime cash flow forecast, an indication as to whether their financial strategy will enable you to achieve your personal lifestyle goals and leave you with a financially secure life, or whether they are likely to run out of capital at some point. We can also build scenarios, test the ''what if'' scenarios invariably rise, such as death of a partner, or enforced retirement due to illness or disability.<br /><br />How powerful would it be for you to know when you could afford to retire, or calculate the sums you need to realise from the sale of the business in order to achieve and/or maintain the desired lifestyle in retirement?</span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><br /><strong>Pension Planning</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">When a marriage or civil partnership breaks down, a pension fund is often one of the major components of the financial settlement. It is important that the treatment of the pension fund is given careful thought and consideration. Our access to impartial advice will help provide a comprehensive overview, including a transfer value analysis if necessary, culminating in a report on the options available, including offset, earmarking and pension sharing orders.<br /><br />Where a pension sharing order is awarded we provide access to all the necessary impartial advice, assessing a suitable future investment strategy and administrative support to complete the transaction to a personal pension arrangement.<br /><br /><strong>Financial Protection</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">The death, serious illness or loss of employment of a divorced spouse and/or parent can have disastrous financial consequences for dependents who have been awarded earmarking orders. Serious consideration should be given to protecting term maintenance payments, or at the very least these issues discussed and offered to every client at risk.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>Business Protection</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Why do business owners insure the desk they sit behind, but not the Key Person, the income generator sat behind it? It is fact that the vast majority of businesses in the UK do not have adequate protection for their most valuable assets, that is, their Key Personnel. We have access to considerable experience in advising business owners on Key Man Protection and Partnership/Shareholder Protection. Where necessary we can assist with draft wordings of Cross/Double Option Agreements and business trust documentation to mitigate the effects of CGT and IHT.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>Lifetime Cash Flow Forecasting</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">We offer our clients access to a comprehensive financial plan.&nbsp;&nbsp;This includes a valuable lifetime cash flow forecast, which is an indication as to whether your financial strategy will enable&nbsp;you to achieve your personal lifestyle goals and leave you secure for life, or whether&nbsp;you are likely to run out of capital at some point. We can also test the most common ''what if'' scenarios such as death of a partner, or enforced retirement due to illness or disability.<br /><br />How powerful would it be to be able to advise business owners when deciding if and when they could afford to retire, or calculate the sum they needed to realise from the sale of the business in order to achieve and/or maintain the desired lifestyle in retirement?</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><em>Banner Jones Wealth Management is:</em></p>\r\n<p><em>-the trading name of Banner Jones Wealth Management LLP (registered in England &amp; Wales, number OC380075)</em></p>\r\n<p><em>-a separate&nbsp;legal entity&nbsp;to Banner&nbsp;Jones ltd</em></p>\r\n<p><em>-is not a law firm&nbsp;authorised or regulated by the Solicitors Regulation Authority</em></p>\r\n<p><em>-an&nbsp;&nbsp;Appointed Representative of Future Life Wealth Management Ltd which is authorised and regulated by the Financial&nbsp;Conduct &nbsp;Authority.</em></p>', '2013-02-14 09:16:16', '2014-07-08 14:16:20', '', '', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0, '<p>Your Wealth...</p>\r\n<p>In Good Hands</p>', '178_BJ_WEALTH_MANAGEMENT_WHITE.JPG', 'image/jpeg', 45123, '2013-03-19 09:26:43', '', 'family_highlight', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', '', NULL, 'family_highlight', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 1, '', '', ''),
(184, 'Legal Costing', 'legal_costing_', 'Legal Costing', 122, 0, 0, 0, '2010-04-29 08:55:42', '<p>Our&nbsp;team of Costs Specialists represent clients in all types&nbsp;of&nbsp;costs proceedings.</p>\r\n<p>Our aim is to maximise the recovery of costs&nbsp;in cases where an order for costs is made in the client''s favour or where an order for&nbsp;costs is made against the client to&nbsp;reduce the level of costs payable.</p>\r\n<p>The services we provide include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Preparation&nbsp;of schedules of costs and subsequent negotiation</li>\r\n<li>Preparation of detailed bills of costs for assessment at court</li>\r\n<li>Preparation of Points of Dispute to the Bill of Costs</li>\r\n<li>Preparation of Replies to Points of Dispute along with subsequent negotiation.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>In the event that agreement cannot be reach&nbsp;without recourse to the court we will arrange for Costs Counsel to&nbsp;attend&nbsp;at the Detailed Assessment hearing.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">LEGAL AID COSTS</span></strong></p>\r\n<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;">FAMILY </span></p>\r\n<p>Claim 1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 4.5% of profit costs &ndash; minimum charge &pound;40</p>\r\n<p>Detailed bill &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pre 01.07.08 certificates - 4.5% of profit costs &ndash; minimum charge &pound;90</p>\r\n<p>Post 01.07.08 certificates &ndash; Prescribed rates (claimed in bill)</p>\r\n<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;">CARE </span></p>\r\n<p>Claim 1A &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 4.5% of profit costs</p>\r\n<p>Detailed bill&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pre 01.10.07 - 4.5% of profit costs &ndash; minimum charge &pound;90</p>\r\n<p>Post 01.10.07 - Prescribed rates (claimed in bill) save where case not exceptional 4.5% of profit costs</p>\r\n<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;">CIVIL </span></p>\r\n<p>Claim 1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 4.5% of profit costs</p>\r\n<p>Detailed bill&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Prescribed rates (claimed in bill)</p>\r\n<p>Legal aid assessment certificates - &pound;20</p>\r\n<p>High costs case plans &ndash; prescribed rates (claimed in bill)</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;">CRIME</span></p>\r\n<p>Litigator fee claims (LF1) - &pound;25</p>\r\n<p>Litigator fee appeals (LF2) - &pound;15</p>\r\n<p>Advocacy fee claims (AF1) - &pound;20</p>\r\n<p>Assessed bills (5144) &ndash; 4.5% of profit costs &ndash; minimum charge of &pound;40</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">LITIGATION COSTS</span></strong></p>\r\n<p>Allocation and listing questionnaire estimates of costs</p>\r\n<p>N260 summary assessment schedule of costs</p>\r\n<p>Schedule of costs for negotiation</p>\r\n<p>Detailed bills of costs for assessment</p>\r\n<p>Request for default costs certificates</p>\r\n<p>Points of dispute to bill of costs</p>\r\n<p>Replies to points of dispute</p>\r\n<p>Negotiation and formulating part 47 offers</p>\r\n<p>Brief to costs counsel</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>We can offer our services on a discounted CCFA so to limit your costs to those that are recovered from the opponent or &pound;100 per hour where your costs are not recoverable from the opponent.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">COURT OF PROTECTION COSTS</span></strong></p>\r\n<p>Short form bills - &pound;50</p>\r\n<p>Detailed bill for provisional assessment &ndash; (Grade D SCCO Guideline rates as claimed in bill)<strong></strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '2011-02-17 16:36:46', '2013-02-19 11:17:23', '', '', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0, '<p>Our Legal Costing Team</p>', '173_Kerry n Serena costing pic.JPG', 'image/jpeg', 202344, '2013-02-19 11:17:23', '', 'family_highlight', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', '', NULL, 'family_highlight', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 0, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(185, 'Legal Expenses Insurance', 'legal_expenses_insurance', 'Legal Expenses Insurance', 178, 0, 0, 1, '2010-04-29 08:55:42', '<h1>Funding</h1>\r\n<h2>Union Funding</h2>\r\n<p>It is common for&nbsp;professionals to seek advice and assistance from their union in the first instance but sometimes there are limitations on the extent of advice and assistance available. Often the union can make it problematic for a professional to seek their own independent solicitor of choice. Union or insurance company panel solicitors are often busy and over worked and may not have a specialism in the area in question.</p>\r\n<h2>Do you have Legal Expenses Insurance?</h2>\r\n<p>It is important to note that the Insurance Companies ( Legal Expenses Insurance ) Regulations 1990 provide that insured persons should be free to select a solicitor of their own choice. Insurance contracts often stipulate that this cover is only available or can be exercised only where legal proceedings have actually been issued. It is sometimes extended to the period before then when investigations or enquiries are underway. Guidance from the Financial Ombudsman is such that insured persons <strong>should be free to request a solicitor of their own choosing where cases are complex or involve particularly difficult or sensitive issues or which involve employment disputes</strong>. Check the terms of your policy as to the extent of cover and any exclusions or limitations.</p>\r\n<p><strong>We can guide you further in relation to this aspect if you think you might be able to receive assistance in funding your legal advice and representation from us</strong>.</p>\r\n<p>We will tailor our service to meet your most pressing needs&nbsp;whilst keeping an eye on &nbsp;your budget.&nbsp; With this in mind, &nbsp;we can often offer you a fixed fee. It may be you need full representation to deal with an interview or hearing/Tribunal, or it It may be limited to advice and assistance in drafting responses or submissions, but whatever you need we''ll be here for you every step of the way</p>', '2013-03-04 10:55:20', '2013-03-25 11:25:18', '', '', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0, '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 'family_highlight', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', NULL, '', '', NULL, 'family_highlight', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 0, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(186, 'CRB Disclosures', 'crb_disclosures', 'CRB Disclosures', 179, 0, 0, 1, '2010-04-29 08:55:42', '<h2>Have you had&nbsp;information revealed on your record as a result of a CRB (DBS*)&nbsp;disclosure that you did not expect?</h2>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Is this affecting&nbsp;your current post, a &nbsp;job application or a volunteer opportunity?</p>\r\n<p>In some cases it may be possible to prepare a challenge or dispute.&nbsp; It may even be possible to delete certain aspects of the record or evidence held by the police.&nbsp; Often we are successful in achieving a revised summary of the information which is more favourable to the individual''s version of events.</p>\r\n<p>We have advised and assisted people across the diverse range of professions from teachers and teaching assistants, doctors and nursing staff, those working in the social care sector and even those who are seeking to volunteer rather than apply for paid work.</p>\r\n<p>Each&nbsp;case is unique.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We can provide you with an initial confidential screening call where we can discuss the avenues open to you and the relative merits of your case.&nbsp;&nbsp; For a more general guide to challenging CRBs <a href="../../../assets/stored_documents/original/42_CRB Factsheet.pdf?1374664709" target="_blank">click here to download our factsheet</a></p>\r\n<p>*Disclosure and Barring Service <a href="../../../page/disclosure-and-barring-service" target="_blank">READ MORE</a></p>', '2013-03-25 11:33:22', '2013-08-12 10:58:50', '', '', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0, '<p>Do you have an issue with a CRB disclosure?</p>\r\n<p>Not sure where to turn?</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '52_iStock_000000751879XSmall.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 147335, '2013-03-25 11:54:50', '', 'family_highlight', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '/team_members/52', '', NULL, 'family_highlight', '', '/team_members/52', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 0, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(187, 'Disclosure and Barring Service', 'disclosure_and_barring_service', 'Disclosure and Barring Service', 180, 0, 0, 1, '2010-04-29 08:55:42', '<h2><span style="font-family: Calibri; color: #000000; font-size: small;">The Disclosure and Barring Service (DBS) formed from the merger between the Criminal Records Bureau (CRB) and the Independent Safeguarding Authority on 1/12/12</span></h2>\r\n<p><span style="font-family: Calibri; color: #000000; font-size: small;">The service combines criminal records checking and barring applications.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-family: Calibri; color: #000000; font-size: small;">The purpose behind applications to bar is to prevent unsuitable persons working with vulnerable people including children. There are two lists maintained one for vulnerable adults and one for children.</span></p>\r\n<p><strong><span style="font-family: Calibri; color: #000000; font-size: small;">We are here to help those who may be facing an application to prevent them from working with one or both of these groups of people.</span></strong></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-family: Calibri; color: #000000; font-size: small;">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Calibri;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Common scenarios</span> include referrals made by schools in respect of volunteers or staff by care homes or hospitals, in respect of staff or volunteers </span></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-family: Calibri; color: #000000; font-size: small;">They include a variety of <span style="text-decoration: underline;">allegations </span>often by pupils eg inappropriate touching or failing to maintain professional boundaries; acts of violence; sexual activity; inappropriate communications or relationships with pupils or patients.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-family: Calibri; color: #000000; font-size: small;">They can also be as a result of conduct which occurred outside of work which may have resulted in a <span style="text-decoration: underline;">Caution, Reprimand or Conviction</span> eg assault or possession of indecent material.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Calibri;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Referrals</span> can be made even where the matter in question was not referred to the police or if it was, was not made subject to a formal police investigation or resulted in any criminal proceedings. Many applications start in disciplinary processes conducted &nbsp;for example by a Care Home, Hospital or School.</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-family: Calibri; color: #000000; font-size: small;">Consideration must be given to whether or not the person has harmed, or may harm or could put people at risk of harm. It is a complex area and each case must be decided on its own unique facts and circumstances. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-family: Calibri; color: #000000; font-size: small;">The consequences are very serious. Many find their chosen field of work or professional career is threatened. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-family: Calibri; color: #000000; font-size: small;">Even if the decision is made that an individual is not to be placed on a barred list the information behind the referral or disclosure can find its way on to the CRB certificate which can in turn affect your employment prospects.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-family: Calibri; color: #000000; font-size: small;">It is important to defend these applications and to seek professional help.</span></p>\r\n<p><strong><span style="font-family: Calibri; color: #000000; font-size: small;">We have an understanding of how difficult these matters are and combine specialist help with a sensitive approach to help you through this process and to prepare a response and the documents you need. </span></strong></p>', '2013-04-22 10:34:22', '2013-07-23 10:21:08', '', '', 2, 2, 0, NULL, 1, 0, '<p>For a confidential chat about your circumstances</p>\r\n<p>call me today</p>', '192_Rachel buckley large.JPG', 'image/jpeg', 115337, '2013-07-23 10:20:05', '', 'family_highlight', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', NULL, '/team_members/52', '', NULL, 'family_highlight', '', '/team_members/52', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 0, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(188, 'Family Assist Scheme', 'family_assist_scheme', 'Family Assist Scheme', 181, 0, 0, 0, '2010-04-29 08:55:42', '<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;The Family Assist Scheme is designed to bridge the funding gap left by the changes to Legal Aid.&nbsp; It is based on the previous Legal Aid criteria and will be used to identify those whose income and capital resources are limited and who may benefit from a scheme assisted reduction in their family law fees.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">The eligibility test consists of&nbsp;three stages:</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Capital Assessment;</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Income Assessment;</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Affordability Test.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">The capital and income eligibility is broadly in line with the funding limits set prior to 1 April 2013.&nbsp; The affordability test takes into consideration debts and other outgoings that you are committed to which my affect your ability to pay for the services that you require.&nbsp; If it was felt that, looking at your overall financial circumstances, you were able to contribute towards the legal fees that you are likely to incur then, on the basis that you set up a standing order at an agreed rate and sign a Notice of Acting in Person, which we can hold on the file for us to use should we require it, then we will sign you up to Family Assist, as long as you are within the relevant capital and income criteria.&nbsp; If we sign you up to Family Assist, then we will charge &pound;99 per hour plus VAT.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">If it was felt that, due to debts and other outgoings, you would not be able to contribute towards your legal fees but that you had somebody else who was willing to pay those fees for you, such as relative, partner or friend, then you may benefit from the scheme and the reduced charging rate provided there is a suitable signed guarantee form from the payer, together with a standing order mandate form at an agreed rate and a Notice of Acting in Person.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Once these are in place, the Family Assist reduced charging rate would apply to your matter.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Please note that, should the standing order mandate form be stopped or unpaid by the bank, the reduced rate will cease and Banner Jones will be entitled, with immediate effect, to cease all further work until such time as the payments are re-started, to lodge the Notice of Acting in Person form with the Court and to apply the fee earner&rsquo;s normal charging rate to any work already carried out and to include these increased fees in any final account.</p>', '2013-04-22 13:47:55', '2014-02-27 09:13:03', '', '', 2, 5, 0, NULL, 1, 0, 'Giving you a helping hand', 'family_assist_logo_FINAL_WHITE.JPG', 'image/pjpeg', 61259, '2013-04-22 14:40:48', '', 'family_highlight', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '/web/contact_us', '', NULL, 'family_highlight', '', '/web/contact_us', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 0, '', '', NULL),
(189, 'Legal Aid', 'legal_aid', 'Legal Aid', 182, 0, 0, 0, '2010-04-29 08:55:42', '<h2><strong>&nbsp;Legal Aid is still available in some cases:</strong></h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>If your case is in relation to children, where the Local Authority Social Services are taking Care Proceedings in relation to those children, then funding is still available.</li>\r\n<li>Domestic Violence Injunction Cases, where you need protection from somebody who is being violent or abusive towards you.</li>\r\n<li>Cases relating to Divorce, financial matters and children, where there is evidence of domestic violence.</li>\r\n<li>Cases in relation to Residence and Contact of children, where there is evidence of child abuse.</li>\r\n<li>Child Abduction.</li>\r\n<li>Representation for a child in Private Family Cases.</li>\r\n<li>Legal advice in support of mediation (no evidence of domestic violence is needed).</li>\r\n<li>Forced Marriage Protection Order Cases.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Is That It?</strong></p>\r\n<p>Yes.&nbsp; For most people, where there is no domestic violence within the relationship, or domestic violence that can be proved to the standard required by the Legal Aid Authority, there is no Public Funding available for Divorce, Dissolution of Civil Partnerships, financial matters and children matters.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<span style="text-decoration: underline;">What Counts as Evidence for Domestic Violence</span>?</p>\r\n<p>The Legal Aid Authority will accept the following evidence of domestic violence.&nbsp; This must be provided by you before we are able to sign you up to any form of Legal Aid, unless you are looking for Help with Mediation, a Domestic Violence Injunction or Local Authority Care Proceedings relating to children.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;A&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Your opponent has a relevant unspent conviction for a domestic violence offence;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;B&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Your opponent has a relevant police caution for a domestic violence offence, given to him or her within the 24 month period immediately before the date of the application for Legal Aid;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;C&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Evidence of relevant criminal proceedings against your opponent for a domestic violence offence, which are still going through the Court and have not finished;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;D&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A relevant protective Injunction Order against your opponent, which is in force or which was granted within the last 24 month period immediately preceding the date of your application for Legal Aid;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;E&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; An undertaking by your opponent within 24 months immediately preceding the date of the application for Legal Aid, provided always that you did not give an undertaking in the same or similar terms at the same time (known as cross undertakings);</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;F&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A letter from the person appointed Chair of a Multi-Agency Risk Assessment Conference, confirming that you were referred to the Conference as a high risk of domestic violence and the Conference has, within the last 24 months, put in place a plan to protect you;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;G&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A copy of a Finding of Fact within previous proceedings, within the last 24 months, confirming that there has been domestic violence;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;H&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A letter or report from a Health Professional (GP, Accident and Emergency Doctor, Nurse or Health Visitor) confirming:</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>(i)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; They have examined you within the last 24 months;</p>\r\n<p>(ii)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; They are satisfied that you had injuries or a condition consistent with those of a victim of domestic violence;</p>\r\n<p>(iii)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; They had no reason to believe that your injuries or condition were not caused by domestic violence;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>I&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A letter from a Social Services Department confirming that, within the last 24 months, you have been assessed as being, or are at risk of being, a victim of domestic violence;</p>\r\n<p>J&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A letter or report from a Domestic Violence Support Organisation confirming:</p>\r\n<p>(i)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; That, within the last 24 month period, you were admitted for a period of 24 hours or more to a refuge established for the purpose of providing accommodation for victims of, or those at risk of, domestic violence;</p>\r\n<p>(ii)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The dates on which you were admitted and, where relevant, left the refuge;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>(iii)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; That you were admitted because of allegations of domestic violence.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Please note that the allegations have to be in relation to the person that you are currently having problems with.&nbsp; These allegations cannot be in relation to a previous or different partner.</p>\r\n<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><br /></span>\r\n<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;">What Counts as Evidence that Children are At Risk</span>?</p>\r\n<p>The Legal Aid Authority will accept the following evidence of children being at risk of abuse:</p>\r\n<p>A&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A relevant unspent conviction of your opponent for a child abuse offence;</p>\r\n<p>B&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A relevant police caution of your opponent for a child abuse offence, given within the&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 24 month period immediately before the date for the Legal Aid application;</p>\r\n<p>C&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Evidence of relevant criminal proceedings that are currently ongoing for a child abuse offence against your opponent which have not concluded;</p>\r\n<p>D&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A relevant protective injunction which is in force, or was granted against your opponent within the 24 month period immediately preceding the date of the application for Legal Aid;</p>\r\n<p>E&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A copy Finding of Fact of abuse of a child by your opponent, made in proceedings in the UK, within the 24 month period immediately preceding the application for Legal Aid;</p>\r\n<p>F&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A letter from a Social Services Department in England and Wales (or it&rsquo;s equivalent in Scotland or Northern Ireland) confirming that, within the 24 month period immediately preceding the application for Legal Aid, the child was assessed as being, or at risk of being, a victim of child abuse by your opponent (or a copy of that assessment);</p>\r\n<p>G&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A letter from a Social Services Department in England and Wales (or it&rsquo;s equivalent in Scotland or Northern Ireland) confirming that, within the 24 month period immediately preceding your application, a Child Protection Plan was put in place to protect the child from abuse, or a risk of abuse, by your opponent (or a copy of that plan);</p>\r\n<p>H&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; An application for an injunction described in Paragraph 2 B made with an application for Prohibited Steps Order against your opponent under Section 8 of the Children Act 1989 which has not, at the date of the application for Legal Aid, been decided by the Court.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Please Note</strong></p>\r\n<p>We cannot pay for any of the above evidence to be provided.&nbsp; If there is a charge for producing the evidence, we cannot pay it: you will need to meet these costs yourself and then bring the evidence to us.</p>\r\n<p>Even in urgent cases, we cannot exercise our Delegated Functions and give you an emergency Legal Aid Certificate without the evidence of domestic violence or child abuse as set out above.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>There are standard letters that have been approved by the Ministry of Justice.&nbsp; For more information about this generally and to access those standard letters, please use the following link: <a href="http://www.justice.gov.uk/legal-aid-divorcing-separating-abusive-partner">http://www.justice.gov.uk/legal-aid-divorcing-separating-abusive-partner</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<span style="text-decoration: underline;">Help with Family Mediation</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;There is a new level of Legal Aid available to help give advice to people who are going through the mediation process.&nbsp; This is called Help with Family Mediation.&nbsp; This allows us to provide you with the legal advice whilst you are going through mediation or immediately following a mediation process.&nbsp; You will still need to meet the normal means and merits test, but we will be able to work through this with you.&nbsp; You will need to bring with you the relevant form from your Mediation Service to show that you are currently going through mediation or have been in mediation within the last 3 months.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '2013-04-22 14:18:41', '2014-02-12 14:14:47', '', '', 2, 1, 0, NULL, 1, 0, '<p>If you are not eliglible for Legal Aid our New Family Assist Scheme offers you a service at significantly discounted fees.</p>\r\n<p>Giving you a helping hand</p>', 'family_assist_logo_FINAL_WHITE.JPG', 'image/pjpeg', 61259, '2013-04-22 14:55:28', '', 'family_highlight', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', NULL, '/page/family-assist-scheme', '', NULL, 'family_highlight', '', '/page/family-assist-scheme', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 0, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(190, 'Types of Wills', 'types_of_wills', 'Types of Wills | Probate Solicitors in Sheffield | Banner Jones', 183, 0, 0, 1, '2010-04-29 08:55:42', '<p style="text-align: left;">One size does not fit all when it comes to a Will.&nbsp; There are several types available and we are here to help you decide on which one best suits your needs.&nbsp; No two Wills we write are ever the same but here are&nbsp;some typical examples of the Wills we write.</p>\r\n<h2 style="text-align: left;">Standard Mirror Wills</h2>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">Typically for a husband and wife with a modest estate who want to leave everything to each other and then on to their children.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">A typical scenario would be a husband leaving his whole estate to his wife. If she dies before her husband then his whole estate is divided equally between their adult children. The wife makes a Mirror Will which reflects her husband&rsquo;s<br />Will. This type of Will is suitable for clients who have modest assets and where the adult children are their natural children i.e. there are no step children involved. Clients sometimes are not aware however that if the husband leaves everything to the wife and dies first, then she is free to make a new Will in<br />the future. She may remarry and leave everything to her new husband rather than her children.</p>\r\n<h2 style="text-align: left;">Property Trust Will (Life Interest Will)</h2>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">This type of Will (also known as a Life Interest Trust Will) is suitable for those clients who want to ensure that their share of their main asset i.e. the family home, is inherited by their children.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">The Will ensures that the surviving spouse (who may already own a share of the family home) has the right to live in the property for the rest of his/her life but will not inherit the ownership of the deceased&rsquo;s share of the property. This type of Will is often used where there are step-children involved so that the needs of all family members can be taken into account. Clients who are concerned about the family home being used to pay for the surviving spouse&rsquo;s care home fees can also benefit from this type of Will.</p>\r\n<h2 style="text-align: left;">Wills for Young Children</h2>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">Where the main beneficiaries of the Will are young children then extra provisions are recommended. Careful thought should be given to who will be the Trustees that will look after the assets until the children are old enough to inherit. Parents can appoint Guardians who will be responsible for the day to day care of the children.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">The Guardians and Trustees do not have to be the same people. The age of the Trustees can be a factor &ndash; appointing grandparents who may have to manage the money for over 20 years may not be the answer.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">Very often professional Trustees such as solicitors are the most appropriate Trustees who will invest the money with the benefit of professional expert advice rather than leaving inexperienced Trustees who very often leave the money to sit in a low-interest bearing bank account.</p>\r\n<h2 style="text-align: left;">Specialist Wills</h2>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">There are many types of specialist Wills. A Discretionary trust Will remains a popular choice. This Will places the estate into a flexible type of trust known as a Discretionary Trust. With the right Trustees in place it allows the deceased&rsquo;s estate to be distributed as the family decide in the future. It allows the family to &ldquo;wait and see&rdquo;. Clients who are worried about beneficiaries with financial problems or possible divorces see the benefit of these types of Wills.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">There are also special types of Wills for disabled persons as well as what are often described as Bloodline Wills to ensure that the assets are passed along the bloodline of the family rather than being passed to the spouses or partners of your children or grandchildren.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">Finally Spousal Bypass Trusts and Wills are an increasingly common combination of Trust and Will designed to minimise the Inheritance Tax which can arise as a result of pension benefits passing directly to the spouse.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">If you are unsure as to which type of Will would be best for you and your family then please give us a call and we will be happy to discuss this with you.&nbsp; All of our Wills are tailor made to suit your needs.</p>\r\n<p><strong>For more information, or to arrange an appointment with an expert, call <span class="calltracks_bannerjonescouk-main">0330 017 6309</span></strong>*<strong>&nbsp;or email&nbsp;<a href="mailto:info@bannerjones.co.uk">info@bannerjones.co.uk</a>.</strong></p>\r\n<p>*<strong><sub>calls cost no more than a local 01 number and are included in your mobile minutes.</sub></strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">&nbsp;</p>', '2013-04-24 10:22:56', '2015-07-22 11:17:14', '', '', 2, 1, 0, NULL, 1, 0, 'All of our Wills come with FREE registration on to the Certainty national Wills register', '170_CertaintyNewLogo.JPG', 'image/jpeg', 44954, '2013-04-24 11:00:22', '', 'family_highlight', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', '', '', '', '', 9, 'family_highlight', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 0, '<p><a href="../../../assets/stored_documents/original/61_Family - Wills 2011 - Updated 07.04.14.pdf?1396883400" target="_blank">Download Banner Jones Wills Leaflet</a></p>\r\n<p><img src="../../../assets/stored_images/original/260_Family - Wills 2011.png?1396885003" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="250" /></p>', '', ''),
(191, 'Motoring Defence', 'motoring_defence', 'Motoring Defence', 184, 0, 0, 0, '2010-04-29 08:55:42', '<h2 style="text-align: justify;">Help with Road Traffic Offences</h2>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">With ever advancing technology constantly monitoring our driving, more and more people are finding themselves charged with Road Traffic Offences. Whether it&rsquo;s exceeding the speed limit or one of the many other offences, they all attract penalties which can quite often&nbsp; lead to significant fines, the endorsement of points on driving licences and ultimately the loss of a licence.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">For some people losing their licence may mean losing their job and have other disastrous consequences. Our specialist Motoring Law Team in Chesterfield&nbsp;are experienced in defending or mitigating charges and penalties, often with the result that a driving ban is avoided.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Our specialist Motoring Law team can provide advice and guidance in all motoring matters including:</p>\r\n<ul style="text-align: justify;">\r\n<li>Speeding offences</li>\r\n<li>Driving under the influence of drugs and or alcohol</li>\r\n<li>Dangerous and careless driving</li>\r\n<li>Failing to comply with traffic signals</li>\r\n<li>Defective vehicles</li>\r\n<li>Driving without insurance</li>\r\n<li>Driving whilst disqualified</li>\r\n<li>Using mobile phones</li>\r\n<li>Failing to provide information/stop after an accident</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIf you need fast, reliable and professional advice on how to defend a Road Traffic charge and perhaps avoid conviction or disqualification please contact us. There are instances where challenges can be made but it is crucial that you take legal advice before taking any other action.', '2013-05-01 15:43:43', '2014-01-23 16:38:55', '', '', 2, 1, 0, NULL, 1, 0, 'We could help to save your licence!', '107_iStock_000013404152XSmall.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 42987, '2013-05-01 15:47:20', '', 'family_highlight', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', '', NULL, '', '', NULL, 'family_highlight', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', 0, NULL, NULL, NULL);
